{"title_page": "Bourgeois of Paris", "text_new": "{{copy edit|date=March 2020}}\n\n[[File:Edit de Louis XI confirmant les privil\u00e8ges des bourgeois de Paris. - Archives Nationales - AE-II-478.jpg|thumb|Edict of [[Louis XI of France|Louis XI]] confirming the privileges of the bourgeois of Paris, [[Archives Nationales (France)|National Archives]], AE-II-478.|alt=]]\n[[File:Philippe de Champaigne - The \u00c9chevins of the City of Paris - WGA4707.jpg|thumb|283x283px|The \u00e9chevins of Paris, by [[Philippe de Champaigne]], 1648]]\nIn [[Paris]] (prior to the [[French Revolution]]), for an individual to qualify as a '''bourgeois of Paris''', one needed to be a part of one of the numerous [[Corporation (feudal Europe)|corporations]] or [[guild]]s of that time. Additionally, the same qualification was required in order to exercise public offices, such as [[Provost of the merchants of Paris|provost of the merchants]], [[alderman]] or [[consul]]. To be a [[Bourgeoisie|bourgeois]] of Paris, according to Article 173 of the [[Custom of Paris in New France|Custom of Paris]], one had to have held [[Domicile (law)|domicile]] in Paris as a [[Leasehold estate|tenant]] or as [[Ownership|owner]] for at least a year and a day. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Division|first=Library of Congress European Law division|url=https://books.google.co.il/books?id=ln8tTxwXiQoC&redir_esc=y|title=The Coutumes of France in the Library of Congress: An Annotated Bibliography - Article 173|last2=|first2=|last3=|first3=|date=|publisher=The Lawbook Exchange, Ltd.|year=|isbn=978-1-58477-627-7|location=|pages=|language=fr}}</ref>\n\nThe bourgeois of Paris had privileges as well as duties: they were free from having to pay the [[taille]], however they were required to pay the city [[taxes]], they had to contribute to public [[Charity (practice)|charity]], they had to arm themselves at their own expense, and needed to join the urban [[militia]]. <ref name=\":0\" /> Unlike for the aristocracy, the genealogies of the bourgeois families of Paris are difficult to track down, as are the names of original families have been diluted and mixed to similar, commoner names. {{Original research inline|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Definition ==\n\nAccording to article 173 (previously 129) of the [[Custom of Paris in New France|Custom of Paris]], the \"right of the bourgeoisie\" is acquired in Paris by any person \"living and residing there for a year and a day,\" that is to say, having a personal home and staying there continuously with family, and not making temporary stays for business. This was to be proven by a receipt of rent or personal capitation, and not by renting a room or staying in a furnished hotel. Unlike the bourgeois or citizens of other free cities, Parisians did not need ''[[Letters of Bourgeoisie]]'' to prove their status. <ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn other words, anyone who owned a home in Paris intra-muros as [[Ownership|owner]] or [[Leasehold estate|tenant]], and who resided there for over a year, was a bourgeois of Paris. There were no other conditions such as heritage, [[oath]] or other, unlike in [[Bourgeois of Brussels|Brussels]] at the same period. {{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Duties and privileges of the bourgeois of Paris ==\n\nThese privileges were numerous, diverse, verying greatly from decade to decade. The list published in 1884 in ''[[L'Interm\u00e9diaire des chercheurs et curieux]] (''The Intermediate of the Researchers and Curious) give a glimpse on the variety of these privileges. Laurence Croq, who has dedicated a thesis to the study of the notion of the bourgeois of Paris at the 18th century, explains that this status had a [[wikt:polymorphous|polymorphous]] characteristic.<ref>Laurence Croq, ''Les \u00ab Bourgeois de Paris \u00bb au <abbr>xviii<sup>e</sup></abbr> si\u00e8cle. Identification d'une cat\u00e9gorie sociale polymorphe'', Universit\u00e9 de Paris-I, 1998 \u00a0({{ISBN|2-7295-2567-X}}).</ref> \n\nThe first privilege of the bourgeois of Paris (and more generally of the inhabitants of the ''Vicomt\u00e9 de Paris'') consisted in having their own set of custom rules, the [[Custom of Paris in New France|Coutume de Paris]].\n\nThe second privilege of the bourgeois of Paris was that of the sworn community of merchants organised into bodies and constituted in the city, which had received from the [[List of French monarchs|king]] certain franchises or privileges, such as the right to have a seal, a common fund, and a \"parlour for Bourgeois\" (city hall); the right to defend itself, to close itself, and to administer itself; and the right to have its own justice and its own police force.\n\n=== Privilege of jurisdiction ===\n\nAccording to Article 112 of the [[Custom of Paris in New France|Custom of Paris]], the bourgeois of Paris can not be forced to [[Pleading|plead]] in [[Defense (legal)|defense]] anywhere other than Paris, including in civil matters for purely [[Ius in re|real rights]].\n\n=== Fiscal privileges ===\n\nFiscal privileges were numerous; those maintained until the [[Estates General of 1789|Meeting of the Estates-General in 1789]] include:\n\n* Exemption from the [[Taille]], including income from property in the countryside in the jurisdiction of the ''Vicomt\u00e9 de Paris'' (the bourgeois of [[Versailles, Yvelines|Versailles]], [[Poissy]], [[Lyon]]s, [[Amiens]], [[Bordeaux]], and several other large cities had the same privilege);\n* Exemption from the right of freehold, granted by [[Charles VI of France|Charles VI]] in July 1409 and suppressed by [[Louis XV of France|Louis XV]];\n* Right to [[Wholesaling|wholesale]] the wine of one's own home without the ministry of ''jur\u00e9s-crieurs'' and without being required to register the sale, and to import it into Paris without paying the [[tariff]]s;\n* Exemption from the [[mortmain]] and the right of mortmain on property in mortmain throughout the kingdom.\n\n=== Some privileges identical to those of the Nobility ===\nThe quality of bourgeois of Paris gave some privileges almost equal to those of the [[French nobility|nobility]], the oldest being the exemption from [[mortmain]], then from the [[Taille]]<ref>''L'Interm\u00e9diaire des chercheurs et curieux'', 1864, ''ibidem''.</ref> and freehold, to benefit from the noble guard. At an early period, the bourgeois of Paris had received from [[Charles V of France|King Charles V]] the right to wear [[Helmet (heraldry)|helmet]] and/or [[Crest (heraldry)|crested]] [[Coat of arms|coats of arms]]<ref>Claude de Ferri\u00e8re, ''Des droits de patronage'', Paris chez Nicolas Le Gras, 1686, p. 545 : \u00ab Par un privil\u00e8ge sp\u00e9cial il est permis aux Bourgeois de Paris, par Lettres Patentes du Roy Charles V. du 9 Ao\u00fbt 1391, de se servir des ornemens appartenant \u00e0 l'\u00e9tat de Chevalerie, et de porter les Armes Tymbr\u00e9es, ainsi que les Nobles d'extraction \u00bb ; ''R\u00e9pertoire universel et raisonn\u00e9 de jurisprudence civile, criminelle, canonique et b\u00e9n\u00e9ficiale, Paris, tome premier, 1784, p. 613 : \u00ab On observera seulement que, par cet \u00e9dit, les bourgeois de Paris sont maintenus dans le droit de porter des Armoiries timbr\u00e9es \u00bb ; A.-L. d' Harmonville,'' Dictionnaire des dates, des faits, des lieux et des hommes historiques'', 1843, tome II, p. 757 ; Joseph Nicolas Guyot,'' R\u00e9pertoire universel et raisonn\u00e9 de jurisprudence civile'', 1784 : \u00ab Par une chartre du 9 Ao\u00fbt 1370, Charles V donna \u00e0 tous les bourgeois de Paris les privil\u00e8ges de la Noblesse, avec permission d'avoir des armoiries timbr\u00e9es, de tenir des fiefs et des alleux dans toute l'\u00e9tendue du royaume...... \u00bb.''</ref> and to carry a [[sword]].<ref>''L'Interm\u00e9diaire des chercheurs et curieux'', 1864 : \u00ab Les privil\u00e8ges sont l'exemption de la taille, le port de l'\u00e9p\u00e9e, les armoiries timbr\u00e9es, le titre de bourgeois de Paris ... \u00bb</ref>\n\nAccording to some authors, among whom [[Fran\u00e7ois-Ren\u00e9 de Chateaubriand|Chateaubriand]], \"[[Charles V of France|Charles V]] granted letters of [[French nobility|nobility]] to all the bourgeois of Paris; [[Charles VI of France|Charles VI]], [[Louis XI of France|Louis XI]], [[Francis I of France|Francis I]] and [[Henry II of France|Henry II]], confirmed these letters of nobility. Paris was never a [[Communes of France|commune]], because it was ''franc'' by the mere presence of the king. \"<ref>Chateaubriand, ''Analyse raisonn\u00e9e de l'Histoire de France'', <abbr>p.</abbr> 311.</ref>\n\nThis privilege was definitively restored in 1716, as it remained until the end of the [[Ancien R\u00e9gime]]:\n\n\"[[Charles V of France|Charles V]] granted the nobility to all the bourgeois of Paris; it was confirmed to them by [[Charles VI of France|Charles VI]], [[Louis XI of France|Louis XI]], [[Francis I of France|Francis I]], and [[Henry II of France|Henry II]]. But [[Henry III of France|Henry III]] restricted this privilege in 1577 to the [[Provost of the merchants of Paris|Provost of the Merchants]] and the [[Alderman|Aldermen]] alone. It was suppressed in 1667, restored in 1707; suppressed again in 1715, and finally restored in 1716, as it stands today. \"<ref>Fran\u00e7ois Alexandre Aubert de La Chesnaye-Desbois, Dictionary of the nobility, Foreword, Volume I, Paris, 1770, p. IX.</ref>\n\nThe bourgeois of Paris enjoyed the right to the noble guard, called for them the bourgeois guard.\n\n== Birth of the bourgeoisie in Paris ==\nThe oldest [[Corporation (feudal Europe)|corporations]] or [[guild]]s in Paris were [[Tailor|clothiers]], [[grocers]], [[haberdasher]]s, and [[Fur clothing|furriers]].\n\nWith the water merchants, heirs of the ''nautes of Lut\u00e8ce'' who exercise the [[monopoly]] that holds the [[Basilica of Saint-Denis|Abbey of Saint-Denis]] for the trade along the [[Seine]], and the ''Grande Boucherie'' (Big Butchery), which reunites the owners of farms of the suburbs and those of salting workshops intra and extramurals, they constitute alongside the [[clergy]] and the [[French nobility|nobility]] a [[Third estate|third power]] that will consecrate in 1357 the Great Ordinance of the [[Provost of the merchants of Paris|provost of the merchants]], [[\u00c9tienne Marcel|Etienne Marcel]], and which will become financially decisive, as the will illustrate the [[Cabochien revolt]].\n\nIn 1190, before going on a crusade, [[Philip II of France|King Philippe Auguste]] wrote his [[Will and testament|will]] and placed six \"loyal men\" at the head of the provost: Thibaut Le Riche, Athon de Greve, Evrouin Le Changeur, Robert de Chartres, Baudouin Bruneau and Nicolas Boucel.<ref>Alfred Fierro, ''Histoire et dictionnaire de Paris'', \u00c9ditions Robert Laffont, coll. \u00ab Bouquins \u00bb, 1996, 1 590 <abbr>p.</abbr> ({{ISBN|978-2221078624}}).</ref>\n\nThe ''Livre des m\u00e9tiers'' (Book of [[Tradesman|Trades]]) and the ''Livre de la taille'' (Book of the [[Taille]]), written under the provost of [[\u00c9tienne Boileau]], allow us to better understand this rising bourgeoisie. Holders of registered occupations are considered to be bourgeois.\n\nDuring the 13th century, bourgeois dynasties were built: Sarrazins, Barbette, Bourdon (see rue des Bourdonnais), Pisdoe or Pizdoue, etc.\n\nThe capacity of bourgeois, that is to say of citizen of a city having political rights in opposition to the simple inhabitants, forms the base of the urban organization of cities. This urban system in Europe dates back for many cities still existing today to [[Classical antiquity|Greco-Latin antiquity]], others were founded around the year one thousand.<ref>[[Henri Pirenne]], ''Les villes du Moyen \u00c2ge, essai d\u2019histoire \u00e9conomique et sociale'', Bruxelles, Lamertin, 1927. [2], also : ''Les villes et les institutions urbaines'', Alcan, 1939.</ref> This system of urban civilization developed in parallel to the rural civilization rooted in the [[Neolithic Europe|Neolithic]] era.<ref>(In French) Pierre Bonenfant, professor at the [[Universit\u00e9 libre de Bruxelles|Brussels University]], \"Racines pr\u00e9historiques de la Wallonie\", in ''Histoire de la Wallonie'' published under the direction of [[L\u00e9opold Genicot]], Toulouse, Privat, 1973, p.37-39: <blockquote>Il n'y a pas si longtemps, tout compte fait, que notre Pr\u00e9histoire est r\u00e9volue. Dans l'angle nord-ouest de l'Europe, la vie, durant le haut Moyen \u00c2ge, a ressembl\u00e9 de tr\u00e8s pr\u00e8s, mat\u00e9riellement et socialement, \u00e0 ce qu'elle avait \u00e9t\u00e9 \u00e0 l'\u00e2ge du Fer, soit que la tradition s'en f\u00fbt purement et simplement maintenue, comme ce fut le cas hors des limites de l'Empire romain, soit qu'elle ait repris vigueur, ce qui advint en de\u00e7\u00e0 de ces limites. Dans le domaine des techniques, l'arch\u00e9ologie ne cesse de multiplier les preuves de cette situation. (...) Forges, charronnages ou poteries rurales sont, au d\u00e9but du Moyen \u00c2ge, tout \u00e0 fait dans la tradition de l'\u00e2ge du Fer. Tandis que notre mode traditionnel d'agriculture, fond\u00e9 \u00e0 la fois sur l'\u00e9levage pour la viande et le lait et sur la culture du bl\u00e9, remonte plus haut encore: \u00e0 l'origine m\u00eame du N\u00e9olithique europ\u00e9en continental (Danubien), c'est-\u00e0-dire au Ve mill\u00e9naire au moins. Il n'en va pas autrement du plan dispers\u00e9 de nos villages qui s'oppose \u00e0 l'habitat fortement group\u00e9 que conna\u00eet l'Orient d\u00e8s le N\u00e9olithique. Et la m\u00eame origine vaut pour nos vieilles chaumi\u00e8res aux murs de colombage, hourd\u00e9s de torchis et coiff\u00e9s d'un toit \u00e0 double pente. (...) Ajoutons que nos campagnes ont conserv\u00e9 parfois jusqu'\u00e0 l'aube de la r\u00e9volution industrielle de vieilles techniques protohistoriques. (...) Nous devons donc nous demander s'il n'existe pas quelques tr\u00e8s vieilles continuit\u00e9s plongeant dans la Pr\u00e9histoire qui peuvent conf\u00e9rer \u00e0 la physionomie de la Wallonie actuelle certains traits particuliers.</blockquote></ref>\n\n== Subsisting bourgeois of Paris families ==\n===13th century===\n\n*[[File:Armoiriesgpisdoe.png|24px]] '''Pizdoe''' family, four [[Provost of the merchants of Paris|provost of the merchants]] of Paris. Many [[Alderman|aldermen]]. In the history of the capital, it was the dynasty that ruled Paris during the longest period. The '''P\u00e9do\u00fce''' were also one of the principal landowners of Paris in the thirteenth and fourteenth centuries.\n*'''Bourdon''' family from the rue des Bourdonnais. Two [[Provost of the merchants of Paris|provosts of the merchants.]]\n*'''Marcel''' family, a [[Provost of the merchants of Paris|provost of the merchants]]: [[\u00c9tienne Marcel|Etienne Marcel]], instigator of the [[Cabochien revolt]]. Several [[Alderman|aldermen]].\n*'''Cocatrix''' family, a [[Provost of the merchants of Paris|provost of the merchant]]<nowiki/>s. Several [[Alderman|aldermen]].\n*'''Sarrazin''' family, a provost of the merchants. Several aldermen.\n*'''Barbette''' family, \u00c9tienne Barbette [[Provost of the merchants of Paris|provost of the merchants]] of Paris. Several [[Alderman|aldermen]]. Rue Barbette was created in the 16th century on one of their property.\n\n===16th century ===\n\n* [[File:Famille_Cochin.svg|24px]]  '''Cochin''' family, politicians, a prefect, historians. Founders of the Cochin Hospital.\n\n===17th century===\n\n*'''Chebron''' famille, [[Sieur]] de Bonnegarde and Cardonne. Councilor of the King in the election of Paris. Hereditary Office of Comptroller General, former triennial of the seventh part of the Annuities of the Town Hall. Letters of the bourgeoisie. Anointed on July 24, 1697.\n*[[File:Blason famille de Lens.svg|24px]] [[De Lens family|'''de''' '''Lens''']] family ([[goldsmith]]s of [[Philippe I, Duke of Orl\u00e9ans]].), also [[bourgeois of Brussels]].\n*'''Martin''' '''de Bussy''' and '''Martin''' '''de''' '''Boulancy''' families.\n*[[Israel Silvestre|'''de''' '''Silvestre''']] family.\n*[[File:Blason de la famille Van Dievoet (Bruxelles).svg|24px]] '''[[Vandive family]]''', a branch of the '''[[van Dievoet family]]''', [[bourgeois of Brussels]].\n*[[File:Blason_Brut\u00e9_de_R\u00e9mur.png|24px]] '''Brut\u00e9 de R\u00e9mur''' family, silk merchants.\n\n===18th century  ===\n*'''Simonneau'''-'''Dubreuil''' family (1776). Rue des Saints-P\u00e8res (related to the family of Sauni\u00e8res, including Henry de Sauni\u00e8res, commissioner of sizes and militia stewardship [[Limoges]] around 1740).\n*'''Billon''' family (1702)\n*'''Gaudart''' family\n*'''Rocquet''' family\n*'''Chebrou''' family (1770). Also bourgeois of [[Niort]] (see Chebrou families de La Merich\u00e8re, Chebrou de Beugnon Chebrou La Foucardi\u00e8re, Chebrou des Loges Chebrou Brush, Chebrou Lespinats, Chebrou La Rouliere, Chebrou Petit-Ch\u00e2teau and all collateral family ties).\n*'''Chevauch\u00e9''' family (filiation followed since 1687, documented as bourgeois of Paris since 17317).\n*'''Marguet''' family, from which the theater [[actor]] Amant is born.\n*'''de''' '''Villiers''' family, Jean de Villiers (1712-1786) descendants of [[Painting|painters]].\n*'''de''' '''Gisors''' family, cousin of the de Villiers family,  descendants of [[architect]]s.\n*'''Louis''' family, Claude Germain Louis Devilliers.\n*'''Maill\u00e9''' family, at the origin of the Royal Manufacture of Spalme.\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* Laurence Croq, ''Les \u00ab Bourgeois de Paris \u00bb au XVIIIe si\u00e8cle : identification d'une cat\u00e9gorie sociale polymorphe'', th\u00e8se de doctorat en histoire, Universit\u00e9 de Paris-I, 1998 {{ISBN|2-7295-2567-X}}.\n* [[Jean Favier]], ''Le Bourgeois de Paris au Moyen \u00c2ge'', \u00c9ditions Tallandier, 2012, 670 p. {{ISBN|978-2847348453}}.\n* Mathieu Marraud, ''De la Ville \u00e0 l'\u00c9tat. La bourgeoisie parisienne -XVIIe et XVIIIe si\u00e8cles'', Paris, Albin Michel, coll. \u00ab Biblioth\u00e8que Histoire \u00bb, 2009, 552p. {{ISBN|978-2-226-18707-9}}.\n* Mathieu Marraud, ''La Noblesse de Paris au XVIIIe si\u00e8cle'', Paris, Le Seuil, 2000, 576 p.  {{ISBN|978-2020372107}}.\n* Bonneserre de Saint-Denis, ''Armorial du Parlement de Paris'', 1862.\n\n=== Connected articles ===\n*[[History of Paris]]\n*[[Bourgeois of Brussels]]\n*[[Bourgeoisie of Geneva]]\n*[[Seven Noble Houses of Brussels]]\n*[[Guilds of Brussels]]\n*[[\u00c9tienne Boileau]]\n*[[\u00c9tienne Marcel|Etienne Marcel]] \n*[[Cabochien revolt]]\n*[[Israel Silvestre]]\n*[[Van Dievoet family]]\n\n== Authority ==\nContent in this edit is translated from the existing French Wikipedia article at [[:fr:Bourgeois de Paris]]; see its history for attribution.\n\n<br />\n\n[[Category:History of Paris by period]]\n[[Category:Estates (social groups)]]\n", "text_old": "{{copy edit|date=March 2020}}\n\n[[File:Edit de Louis XI confirmant les privil\u00e8ges des bourgeois de Paris. - Archives Nationales - AE-II-478.jpg|thumb|Edict of [[Louis XI of France|Louis XI]] confirming the privileges of the bourgeois of Paris, [[Archives Nationales (France)|National Archives]], AE-II-478.|alt=]]\n[[File:Philippe de Champaigne - The \u00c9chevins of the City of Paris - WGA4707.jpg|thumb|283x283px|The \u00e9chevins of Paris, by [[Philippe de Champaigne]], 1648]]\nIn [[Paris]] (prior to the [[French Revolution]]), for an individual to qualify as a '''bourgeois of Paris''', one needed to be a part of one of the numerous [[Corporation (feudal Europe)|corporations]] or [[guild]]s of that time. Additionally, the same qualification was required in order to exercise public offices, such as [[Provost of the merchants of Paris|provost of the merchants]], [[alderman]] or [[consul]]. To be a [[Bourgeoisie|bourgeois]] of Paris, according to Article 173 of the [[Custom of Paris in New France|Custom of Paris]], one had to have held [[Domicile (law)|domicile]] in Paris as a [[Leasehold estate|tenant]] or as [[Ownership|owner]] for at least a year and a day. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Division|first=Library of Congress European Law division|url=https://books.google.co.il/books?id=ln8tTxwXiQoC&redir_esc=y|title=The Coutumes of France in the Library of Congress: An Annotated Bibliography - Article 173|last2=|first2=|last3=|first3=|date=|publisher=The Lawbook Exchange, Ltd.|year=|isbn=978-1-58477-627-7|location=|pages=|language=fr}}</ref>\n\nThe bourgeois of Paris had privileges as well as duties: they were free from having to pay the [[taille]], however they were required to pay the city [[taxes]], they had to contribute to public [[Charity (practice)|charity]], they had to arm themselves at their own expenses and to join the urban [[militia]]. <ref name=\":0\" /> Unlike for the aristocracy, the genealogies of the bourgeois families of Paris are difficult to track down, as are the names of original families have been diluted and mixed to similar, commoner names. {{Original research inline|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Definition ==\n\nAccording to article 173 (previously 129) of the [[Custom of Paris in New France|Custom of Paris]], the \"right of the bourgeoisie\" is acquired in Paris by any person \"living and residing there for a year and a day,\" that is to say, having a personal home and staying there continuously with family, and not making temporary stays for business. This was to be proven by a receipt of rent or personal capitation, and not by renting a room or staying in a furnished hotel. Unlike the bourgeois or citizens of other free cities, Parisians did not need ''[[Letters of Bourgeoisie]]'' to prove their status. <ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn other words, anyone who owned a home in Paris intra-muros as [[Ownership|owner]] or [[Leasehold estate|tenant]], and who resided there for over a year, was a bourgeois of Paris. There were no other conditions such as heritage, [[oath]] or other, unlike in [[Bourgeois of Brussels|Brussels]] at the same period. {{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Duties and privileges of the bourgeois of Paris ==\n\nThese privileges were numerous, diverse, verying greatly from decade to decade. The list published in 1884 in ''[[L'Interm\u00e9diaire des chercheurs et curieux]] (''The Intermediate of the Researchers and Curious) give a glimpse on the variety of these privileges. Laurence Croq, who has dedicated a thesis to the study of the notion of the bourgeois of Paris at the 18th century, explains that this status had a [[wikt:polymorphous|polymorphous]] characteristic.<ref>Laurence Croq, ''Les \u00ab Bourgeois de Paris \u00bb au <abbr>xviii<sup>e</sup></abbr> si\u00e8cle. Identification d'une cat\u00e9gorie sociale polymorphe'', Universit\u00e9 de Paris-I, 1998 \u00a0({{ISBN|2-7295-2567-X}}).</ref> \n\nThe first privilege of the bourgeois of Paris (and more generally of the inhabitants of the ''Vicomt\u00e9 de Paris'') consisted in having their own set of custom rules, the [[Custom of Paris in New France|Coutume de Paris]].\n\nThe second privilege of the bourgeois of Paris was that of the sworn community of merchants organised into bodies and constituted in the city, which had received from the [[List of French monarchs|king]] certain franchises or privileges, such as the right to have a seal, a common fund, and a \"parlour for Bourgeois\" (city hall); the right to defend itself, to close itself, and to administer itself; and the right to have its own justice and its own police force.\n\n=== Privilege of jurisdiction ===\n\nAccording to Article 112 of the [[Custom of Paris in New France|Custom of Paris]], the bourgeois of Paris can not be forced to [[Pleading|plead]] in [[Defense (legal)|defense]] anywhere other than Paris, including in civil matters for purely [[Ius in re|real rights]].\n\n=== Fiscal privileges ===\n\nFiscal privileges were numerous; those maintained until the [[Estates General of 1789|Meeting of the Estates-General in 1789]] include:\n\n* Exemption from the [[Taille]], including income from property in the countryside in the jurisdiction of the ''Vicomt\u00e9 de Paris'' (the bourgeois of [[Versailles, Yvelines|Versailles]], [[Poissy]], [[Lyon]]s, [[Amiens]], [[Bordeaux]], and several other large cities had the same privilege);\n* Exemption from the right of freehold, granted by [[Charles VI of France|Charles VI]] in July 1409 and suppressed by [[Louis XV of France|Louis XV]];\n* Right to [[Wholesaling|wholesale]] the wine of one's own home without the ministry of ''jur\u00e9s-crieurs'' and without being required to register the sale, and to import it into Paris without paying the [[tariff]]s;\n* Exemption from the [[mortmain]] and the right of mortmain on property in mortmain throughout the kingdom.\n\n=== Some privileges identical to those of the Nobility ===\nThe quality of bourgeois of Paris gave some privileges almost equal to those of the [[French nobility|nobility]], the oldest being the exemption from [[mortmain]], then from the [[Taille]]<ref>''L'Interm\u00e9diaire des chercheurs et curieux'', 1864, ''ibidem''.</ref> and freehold, to benefit from the noble guard. At an early period, the bourgeois of Paris had received from [[Charles V of France|King Charles V]] the right to wear [[Helmet (heraldry)|helmet]] and/or [[Crest (heraldry)|crested]] [[Coat of arms|coats of arms]]<ref>Claude de Ferri\u00e8re, ''Des droits de patronage'', Paris chez Nicolas Le Gras, 1686, p. 545 : \u00ab Par un privil\u00e8ge sp\u00e9cial il est permis aux Bourgeois de Paris, par Lettres Patentes du Roy Charles V. du 9 Ao\u00fbt 1391, de se servir des ornemens appartenant \u00e0 l'\u00e9tat de Chevalerie, et de porter les Armes Tymbr\u00e9es, ainsi que les Nobles d'extraction \u00bb ; ''R\u00e9pertoire universel et raisonn\u00e9 de jurisprudence civile, criminelle, canonique et b\u00e9n\u00e9ficiale, Paris, tome premier, 1784, p. 613 : \u00ab On observera seulement que, par cet \u00e9dit, les bourgeois de Paris sont maintenus dans le droit de porter des Armoiries timbr\u00e9es \u00bb ; A.-L. d' Harmonville,'' Dictionnaire des dates, des faits, des lieux et des hommes historiques'', 1843, tome II, p. 757 ; Joseph Nicolas Guyot,'' R\u00e9pertoire universel et raisonn\u00e9 de jurisprudence civile'', 1784 : \u00ab Par une chartre du 9 Ao\u00fbt 1370, Charles V donna \u00e0 tous les bourgeois de Paris les privil\u00e8ges de la Noblesse, avec permission d'avoir des armoiries timbr\u00e9es, de tenir des fiefs et des alleux dans toute l'\u00e9tendue du royaume...... \u00bb.''</ref> and to carry a [[sword]].<ref>''L'Interm\u00e9diaire des chercheurs et curieux'', 1864 : \u00ab Les privil\u00e8ges sont l'exemption de la taille, le port de l'\u00e9p\u00e9e, les armoiries timbr\u00e9es, le titre de bourgeois de Paris ... \u00bb</ref>\n\nAccording to some authors, among whom [[Fran\u00e7ois-Ren\u00e9 de Chateaubriand|Chateaubriand]], \"[[Charles V of France|Charles V]] granted letters of [[French nobility|nobility]] to all the bourgeois of Paris; [[Charles VI of France|Charles VI]], [[Louis XI of France|Louis XI]], [[Francis I of France|Francis I]] and [[Henry II of France|Henry II]], confirmed these letters of nobility. Paris was never a [[Communes of France|commune]], because it was ''franc'' by the mere presence of the king. \"<ref>Chateaubriand, ''Analyse raisonn\u00e9e de l'Histoire de France'', <abbr>p.</abbr> 311.</ref>\n\nThis privilege was definitively restored in 1716, as it remained until the end of the [[Ancien R\u00e9gime]]:\n\n\"[[Charles V of France|Charles V]] granted the nobility to all the bourgeois of Paris; it was confirmed to them by [[Charles VI of France|Charles VI]], [[Louis XI of France|Louis XI]], [[Francis I of France|Francis I]], and [[Henry II of France|Henry II]]. But [[Henry III of France|Henry III]] restricted this privilege in 1577 to the [[Provost of the merchants of Paris|Provost of the Merchants]] and the [[Alderman|Aldermen]] alone. It was suppressed in 1667, restored in 1707; suppressed again in 1715, and finally restored in 1716, as it stands today. \"<ref>Fran\u00e7ois Alexandre Aubert de La Chesnaye-Desbois, Dictionary of the nobility, Foreword, Volume I, Paris, 1770, p. IX.</ref>\n\nThe bourgeois of Paris enjoyed the right to the noble guard, called for them the bourgeois guard.\n\n== Birth of the bourgeoisie in Paris ==\nThe oldest [[Corporation (feudal Europe)|corporations]] or [[guild]]s in Paris were [[Tailor|clothiers]], [[grocers]], [[haberdasher]]s, and [[Fur clothing|furriers]].\n\nWith the water merchants, heirs of the ''nautes of Lut\u00e8ce'' who exercise the [[monopoly]] that holds the [[Basilica of Saint-Denis|Abbey of Saint-Denis]] for the trade along the [[Seine]], and the ''Grande Boucherie'' (Big Butchery), which reunites the owners of farms of the suburbs and those of salting workshops intra and extramurals, they constitute alongside the [[clergy]] and the [[French nobility|nobility]] a [[Third estate|third power]] that will consecrate in 1357 the Great Ordinance of the [[Provost of the merchants of Paris|provost of the merchants]], [[\u00c9tienne Marcel|Etienne Marcel]], and which will become financially decisive, as the will illustrate the [[Cabochien revolt]].\n\nIn 1190, before going on a crusade, [[Philip II of France|King Philippe Auguste]] wrote his [[Will and testament|will]] and placed six \"loyal men\" at the head of the provost: Thibaut Le Riche, Athon de Greve, Evrouin Le Changeur, Robert de Chartres, Baudouin Bruneau and Nicolas Boucel.<ref>Alfred Fierro, ''Histoire et dictionnaire de Paris'', \u00c9ditions Robert Laffont, coll. \u00ab Bouquins \u00bb, 1996, 1 590 <abbr>p.</abbr> ({{ISBN|978-2221078624}}).</ref>\n\nThe ''Livre des m\u00e9tiers'' (Book of [[Tradesman|Trades]]) and the ''Livre de la taille'' (Book of the [[Taille]]), written under the provost of [[\u00c9tienne Boileau]], allow us to better understand this rising bourgeoisie. Holders of registered occupations are considered to be bourgeois.\n\nDuring the 13th century, bourgeois dynasties were built: Sarrazins, Barbette, Bourdon (see rue des Bourdonnais), Pisdoe or Pizdoue, etc.\n\nThe capacity of bourgeois, that is to say of citizen of a city having political rights in opposition to the simple inhabitants, forms the base of the urban organization of cities. This urban system in Europe dates back for many cities still existing today to [[Classical antiquity|Greco-Latin antiquity]], others were founded around the year one thousand.<ref>[[Henri Pirenne]], ''Les villes du Moyen \u00c2ge, essai d\u2019histoire \u00e9conomique et sociale'', Bruxelles, Lamertin, 1927. [2], also : ''Les villes et les institutions urbaines'', Alcan, 1939.</ref> This system of urban civilization developed in parallel to the rural civilization rooted in the [[Neolithic Europe|Neolithic]] era.<ref>(In French) Pierre Bonenfant, professor at the [[Universit\u00e9 libre de Bruxelles|Brussels University]], \"Racines pr\u00e9historiques de la Wallonie\", in ''Histoire de la Wallonie'' published under the direction of [[L\u00e9opold Genicot]], Toulouse, Privat, 1973, p.37-39: <blockquote>Il n'y a pas si longtemps, tout compte fait, que notre Pr\u00e9histoire est r\u00e9volue. Dans l'angle nord-ouest de l'Europe, la vie, durant le haut Moyen \u00c2ge, a ressembl\u00e9 de tr\u00e8s pr\u00e8s, mat\u00e9riellement et socialement, \u00e0 ce qu'elle avait \u00e9t\u00e9 \u00e0 l'\u00e2ge du Fer, soit que la tradition s'en f\u00fbt purement et simplement maintenue, comme ce fut le cas hors des limites de l'Empire romain, soit qu'elle ait repris vigueur, ce qui advint en de\u00e7\u00e0 de ces limites. Dans le domaine des techniques, l'arch\u00e9ologie ne cesse de multiplier les preuves de cette situation. (...) Forges, charronnages ou poteries rurales sont, au d\u00e9but du Moyen \u00c2ge, tout \u00e0 fait dans la tradition de l'\u00e2ge du Fer. Tandis que notre mode traditionnel d'agriculture, fond\u00e9 \u00e0 la fois sur l'\u00e9levage pour la viande et le lait et sur la culture du bl\u00e9, remonte plus haut encore: \u00e0 l'origine m\u00eame du N\u00e9olithique europ\u00e9en continental (Danubien), c'est-\u00e0-dire au Ve mill\u00e9naire au moins. Il n'en va pas autrement du plan dispers\u00e9 de nos villages qui s'oppose \u00e0 l'habitat fortement group\u00e9 que conna\u00eet l'Orient d\u00e8s le N\u00e9olithique. Et la m\u00eame origine vaut pour nos vieilles chaumi\u00e8res aux murs de colombage, hourd\u00e9s de torchis et coiff\u00e9s d'un toit \u00e0 double pente. (...) Ajoutons que nos campagnes ont conserv\u00e9 parfois jusqu'\u00e0 l'aube de la r\u00e9volution industrielle de vieilles techniques protohistoriques. (...) Nous devons donc nous demander s'il n'existe pas quelques tr\u00e8s vieilles continuit\u00e9s plongeant dans la Pr\u00e9histoire qui peuvent conf\u00e9rer \u00e0 la physionomie de la Wallonie actuelle certains traits particuliers.</blockquote></ref>\n\n== Subsisting bourgeois of Paris families ==\n===13th century===\n\n*[[File:Armoiriesgpisdoe.png|24px]] '''Pizdoe''' family, four [[Provost of the merchants of Paris|provost of the merchants]] of Paris. Many [[Alderman|aldermen]]. In the history of the capital, it was the dynasty that ruled Paris during the longest period. The '''P\u00e9do\u00fce''' were also one of the principal landowners of Paris in the thirteenth and fourteenth centuries.\n*'''Bourdon''' family from the rue des Bourdonnais. Two [[Provost of the merchants of Paris|provosts of the merchants.]]\n*'''Marcel''' family, a [[Provost of the merchants of Paris|provost of the merchants]]: [[\u00c9tienne Marcel|Etienne Marcel]], instigator of the [[Cabochien revolt]]. Several [[Alderman|aldermen]].\n*'''Cocatrix''' family, a [[Provost of the merchants of Paris|provost of the merchant]]<nowiki/>s. Several [[Alderman|aldermen]].\n*'''Sarrazin''' family, a provost of the merchants. Several aldermen.\n*'''Barbette''' family, \u00c9tienne Barbette [[Provost of the merchants of Paris|provost of the merchants]] of Paris. Several [[Alderman|aldermen]]. Rue Barbette was created in the 16th century on one of their property.\n\n===16th century ===\n\n* [[File:Famille_Cochin.svg|24px]]  '''Cochin''' family, politicians, a prefect, historians. Founders of the Cochin Hospital.\n\n===17th century===\n\n*'''Chebron''' famille, [[Sieur]] de Bonnegarde and Cardonne. Councilor of the King in the election of Paris. Hereditary Office of Comptroller General, former triennial of the seventh part of the Annuities of the Town Hall. Letters of the bourgeoisie. Anointed on July 24, 1697.\n*[[File:Blason famille de Lens.svg|24px]] [[De Lens family|'''de''' '''Lens''']] family ([[goldsmith]]s of [[Philippe I, Duke of Orl\u00e9ans]].), also [[bourgeois of Brussels]].\n*'''Martin''' '''de Bussy''' and '''Martin''' '''de''' '''Boulancy''' families.\n*[[Israel Silvestre|'''de''' '''Silvestre''']] family.\n*[[File:Blason de la famille Van Dievoet (Bruxelles).svg|24px]] '''[[Vandive family]]''', a branch of the '''[[van Dievoet family]]''', [[bourgeois of Brussels]].\n*[[File:Blason_Brut\u00e9_de_R\u00e9mur.png|24px]] '''Brut\u00e9 de R\u00e9mur''' family, silk merchants.\n\n===18th century  ===\n*'''Simonneau'''-'''Dubreuil''' family (1776). Rue des Saints-P\u00e8res (related to the family of Sauni\u00e8res, including Henry de Sauni\u00e8res, commissioner of sizes and militia stewardship [[Limoges]] around 1740).\n*'''Billon''' family (1702)\n*'''Gaudart''' family\n*'''Rocquet''' family\n*'''Chebrou''' family (1770). Also bourgeois of [[Niort]] (see Chebrou families de La Merich\u00e8re, Chebrou de Beugnon Chebrou La Foucardi\u00e8re, Chebrou des Loges Chebrou Brush, Chebrou Lespinats, Chebrou La Rouliere, Chebrou Petit-Ch\u00e2teau and all collateral family ties).\n*'''Chevauch\u00e9''' family (filiation followed since 1687, documented as bourgeois of Paris since 17317).\n*'''Marguet''' family, from which the theater [[actor]] Amant is born.\n*'''de''' '''Villiers''' family, Jean de Villiers (1712-1786) descendants of [[Painting|painters]].\n*'''de''' '''Gisors''' family, cousin of the de Villiers family,  descendants of [[architect]]s.\n*'''Louis''' family, Claude Germain Louis Devilliers.\n*'''Maill\u00e9''' family, at the origin of the Royal Manufacture of Spalme.\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* Laurence Croq, ''Les \u00ab Bourgeois de Paris \u00bb au XVIIIe si\u00e8cle : identification d'une cat\u00e9gorie sociale polymorphe'', th\u00e8se de doctorat en histoire, Universit\u00e9 de Paris-I, 1998 {{ISBN|2-7295-2567-X}}.\n* [[Jean Favier]], ''Le Bourgeois de Paris au Moyen \u00c2ge'', \u00c9ditions Tallandier, 2012, 670 p. {{ISBN|978-2847348453}}.\n* Mathieu Marraud, ''De la Ville \u00e0 l'\u00c9tat. La bourgeoisie parisienne -XVIIe et XVIIIe si\u00e8cles'', Paris, Albin Michel, coll. \u00ab Biblioth\u00e8que Histoire \u00bb, 2009, 552p. {{ISBN|978-2-226-18707-9}}.\n* Mathieu Marraud, ''La Noblesse de Paris au XVIIIe si\u00e8cle'', Paris, Le Seuil, 2000, 576 p.  {{ISBN|978-2020372107}}.\n* Bonneserre de Saint-Denis, ''Armorial du Parlement de Paris'', 1862.\n\n=== Connected articles ===\n*[[History of Paris]]\n*[[Bourgeois of Brussels]]\n*[[Bourgeoisie of Geneva]]\n*[[Seven Noble Houses of Brussels]]\n*[[Guilds of Brussels]]\n*[[\u00c9tienne Boileau]]\n*[[\u00c9tienne Marcel|Etienne Marcel]] \n*[[Cabochien revolt]]\n*[[Israel Silvestre]]\n*[[Van Dievoet family]]\n\n== Authority ==\nContent in this edit is translated from the existing French Wikipedia article at [[:fr:Bourgeois de Paris]]; see its history for attribution.\n\n<br />\n\n[[Category:History of Paris by period]]\n[[Category:Estates (social groups)]]\n", "name_user": "Ccvegso", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bourgeois_of_Paris"}
{"title_page": "Southfield School, Kettering", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name          = Southfield School\n| image         = Logo_of_Southfield_School_in_Kettering,_England,_Jan_2014.png\n| image_size          = \n| coordinates   = {{coord|52.3866|-0.7181|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n| motto         = \u201csilence ladies\u201d\n| established   =1976\n| type          = [[Academy (English school)|Academy]]\n| religious_affiliation      =\n| president     =\n| head_label    = Headteacher \n| head          = Steph Roberts\n| r_head_label  =\n| r_head        =\n| chair_label   =\n| chair         =\n| founder       =\n| address        = Lewis Road\n| city          = [[Kettering]]\n| county        = [[Northamptonshire]]\n| country       = England\n| postcode      = NN15 6HE\n| ofsted        = yes\n| dfeno         = 928/5400\n| urn           = 136976 \n| staff         =\n| enrolment    = \n| gender        = Girls<br>''([[Mixed-sex education|Coeducational]] sixth form)''\n| lower_age     = 11\n| upper_age     = 18\n| houses        = Currently none.\n| colours       = \n| publication   =\n| website       = http://www.southfieldsch.co.uk/\n}}\n\n'''Southfield School'''  (formerly known as Southfield School for Girls) is a girls' [[secondary school]] and [[Mixed-sex education|coeducational]] [[sixth form]] with [[Academy (English school)|academy status]], located in [[Kettering]] in the [[English county]] of [[Northamptonshire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southfieldsch.co.uk/ |title=Southfield School |publisher=Southfieldsch.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2014-01-04}}</ref>\n\nPreviously a [[foundation school]] administered by [[Northamptonshire County Council]], the school converted to academy status in August 2011. The school continues to coordinate with Northamptonshire County Council for admissions.\n\nSouthfield School offers [[General Certificate of Secondary Education|GCSEs]] as programmes of study for girls. The school operates a coeducational sixth form, where students can choose to study from range of [[GCE Advanced Level|A Levels]] and [[Business and Technology Education Council|BTECs]].\n\n==Notable former pupils==\n*[[Faryl Smith]], mezzo-soprano<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.northantstelegraph.co.uk/news/top-stories/kettering-elvis-impersonator-aged-seven-to-appear-on-britain-s-got-talent-1-794745 |title=Kettering Elvis impersonator, aged seven, to appear on Britain's Got Talent - Northamptonshire Telegraph |publisher=Northantstelegraph.co.uk |date=2008-10-22 |accessdate=2014-01-04}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.southfieldsch.co.uk/ Southfield School official website]\n\n{{Schools in Northamptonshire}}\n\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Northamptonshire]]\n[[Category:Girls' schools in Northamptonshire]]\n[[Category:Academies in Northamptonshire]]\n\n\n{{Northamptonshire-school-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name          = Southfield School\n| image         = Logo_of_Southfield_School_in_Kettering,_England,_Jan_2014.png\n| image_size          = \n| coordinates   = {{coord|52.3866|-0.7181|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n| motto         = Challenge, Commitment, Choice\n| established   =1976\n| type          = [[Academy (English school)|Academy]]\n| religious_affiliation      =\n| president     =\n| head_label    = Headteacher \n| head          = Steph Roberts\n| r_head_label  =\n| r_head        =\n| chair_label   =\n| chair         =\n| founder       =\n| address        = Lewis Road\n| city          = [[Kettering]]\n| county        = [[Northamptonshire]]\n| country       = England\n| postcode      = NN15 6HE\n| ofsted        = yes\n| dfeno         = 928/5400\n| urn           = 136976 \n| staff         =\n| enrolment    = \n| gender        = Girls<br>''([[Mixed-sex education|Coeducational]] sixth form)''\n| lower_age     = 11\n| upper_age     = 18\n| houses        = Currently none.\n| colours       = \n| publication   =\n| website       = http://www.southfieldsch.co.uk/\n}}\n\n'''Southfield School'''  (formerly known as Southfield School for Girls) is a girls' [[secondary school]] and [[Mixed-sex education|coeducational]] [[sixth form]] with [[Academy (English school)|academy status]], located in [[Kettering]] in the [[English county]] of [[Northamptonshire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southfieldsch.co.uk/ |title=Southfield School |publisher=Southfieldsch.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2014-01-04}}</ref>\n\nPreviously a [[foundation school]] administered by [[Northamptonshire County Council]], the school converted to academy status in August 2011. The school continues to coordinate with Northamptonshire County Council for admissions.\n\nSouthfield School offers [[General Certificate of Secondary Education|GCSEs]] as programmes of study for girls. The school operates a coeducational sixth form, where students can choose to study from range of [[GCE Advanced Level|A Levels]] and [[Business and Technology Education Council|BTECs]].\n\n==Notable former pupils==\n*[[Faryl Smith]], mezzo-soprano<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.northantstelegraph.co.uk/news/top-stories/kettering-elvis-impersonator-aged-seven-to-appear-on-britain-s-got-talent-1-794745 |title=Kettering Elvis impersonator, aged seven, to appear on Britain's Got Talent - Northamptonshire Telegraph |publisher=Northantstelegraph.co.uk |date=2008-10-22 |accessdate=2014-01-04}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.southfieldsch.co.uk/ Southfield School official website]\n\n{{Schools in Northamptonshire}}\n\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Northamptonshire]]\n[[Category:Girls' schools in Northamptonshire]]\n[[Category:Academies in Northamptonshire]]\n\n\n{{Northamptonshire-school-stub}}\n", "name_user": "86.190.128.134", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Southfield_School,_Kettering"}
{"title_page": "Povl Erik Carstensen", "text_new": "{{Infobox comedian\n| name    =Povl Erik Carstensen \n| image =    \n|  imagesize         = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = \n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1960|6|8}}<ref name=\"danskefilm\"/>\n| birth_place       =[[Vangede]], [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]<ref name=\"BT\"/>\n| medium            = \n| nationality       = [[Danish people|Danish]]\n| active            = 1982\u2013present\n| genre             = \n| subject           = \n| influences        =\n| influenced        = \n| spouse            = \n| notable_work      = \n| website           = \n| baftaawards       =\n| britishcomedyawards =\n}}\n'''Povl Erik Carstensen''' (born June 8, 1960<ref name=\"danskefilm\">http://m.danskefilm.dk/skuespiller.php?id=3638</ref> in [[Vangede]]<ref name=\"BT\">http://www.gyldendal.dk/forfattere/povl-erik-carstensen-f26633</ref>) is a Danish comedian, actor and jazz [[double bass]]ist. Appearing both on film and TV and as a live stand-up, he is best known for his role as Aage in the comic duo of [[John and Aage]] on [[TV 2 (Denmark)|TV 2]], alongside [[Morten Lorentzen]] and for his work with [[Thomas Wivel]]. He directed and starred in the film ''[[Holes in the Soup]]'' in 1988 featuring John and Aage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.danskefilm.dk/film/783.html|title=Huller i suppen|publisher=Danske Film|accessdate=August 29, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Etv\u00e6relses med spisetoilet - En stand-up encyklop\u00e6di'' (1996)\n* ''Historien om hvorfor dyrene siger, som de siger'' (1997)\n* ''Ventetiden er gratis - En stand-up encyklop\u00e6di II'' (1998)\n* ''Hvad enhver kvinde b\u00f8r vide om m\u00e6nd'' with [[Thomas Wivel]] (2005)\n* ''Hvad enhver mand b\u00f8r vide om kvinder'' with [[Thomas Wivel]] (2005)\n* ''Hvordan man overlever sin kones graviditet \u2013 En guide til frustrerede m\u00e6nd'' with [[Thomas Wivel]] (2006)\n* ''Det mest pinlige - Danskere fort\u00e6ller om sex om samliv'' with [[Thomas Wivel]] (2007)\n\n==Filmography==\n*''[[Huller i suppen]]'' (1988)\n*''Casanova'' (1990)\n*''De frigjorte'' (1993)\n*''Smukke dreng'' (1993)\n*''N\u00e6ste skridt'' (2005)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.povlerikcarstensen.dk/ Official site]\n* {{IMDb name|nm0141381|name=Povl Erik Carstensen}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carstensen, Povl}}\n[[Category:Danish comedians]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Vangede]]\n[[Category:Danish jazz double-bassists]]\n[[Category:Male double-bassists]]\n[[Category:21st-century double-bassists]]\n[[Category:21st-century male musicians]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n\n\n{{Denmark-actor-stub}}\n{{comedian-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox comedian\n| name    =Povl Erik Carstensen \n| image =    \n|  imagesize         = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = \n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1960|6|8}}<ref name=\"danskefilm\"/>\n| birth_place       =[[Vangede]], [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]<ref name=\"BT\"/>\n| medium            = \n| nationality       = [[Danish people|Danish]]\n| active            = 1982\u2013present\n| genre             = \n| subject           = \n| influences        =\n| influenced        = \n| spouse            = \n| notable_work      = \n| website           = \n| baftaawards       =\n| britishcomedyawards =\n}}\n'''Povl Erik Carstensen''' (born June 8, 1960<ref name=\"danskefilm\">http://m.danskefilm.dk/skuespiller.php?id=3638</ref> in [[Vangede]]<ref name=\"BT\">http://www.gyldendal.dk/forfattere/povl-erik-carstensen-f26633</ref>) is a Danish comedian, actor and jazz [[double bass]]ist. Appearing both on film and TV and as a live stand-up, he is best known for his role as Aage in the comic duo of [[John and Aage]] on [[TV 2 (Denmark)|TV 2]], alongside [[Morten Lorentzen]] and for his work with [[Thomas Wivel]]. He directed and starred in the film ''[[Holes in the Soup]]'' in 1988 featuring John and Aage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.danskefilm.dk/film/783.html|title=Huller i suppen|publisher=Danske Film|accessdate=August 29, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Etv\u00e6relses med spisetoilet - En stand-up encyklop\u00e6di'' (1996)\n* ''Historien om hvorfor dyrene siger, som de siger'' (1997)\n* ''Ventetiden er gratis - En stand-up encyklop\u00e6di II'' (1998)\n* ''Hvad enhver kvinde b\u00f8r vide om m\u00e6nd'' with [[Thomas Wivel]] (2005)\n* ''Hvad enhver mand b\u00f8r vide om kvinder'' with [[Thomas Wivel]] (2005)\n* ''Hvordan man overlever sin kones graviditet \u2013 En guide til frustrerede m\u00e6nd'' with [[Thomas Wivel]] (2006)\n* ''Det mest pinlige - Danskere fort\u00e6ller om sex om samliv'' with [[Thomas Wivel]] (2007)\n\n==Filmography==\n*''[[Huller i suppen]]'' (1988)\n*''Casanova'' (1990)\n*''De frigjorte'' (1993)\n*''Smukke dreng'' (1993)\n*''N\u00e6ste skridt'' (2005)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.povlerikcarstensen.dk/ Official site]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carstensen, Povl}}\n[[Category:Danish comedians]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Vangede]]\n[[Category:Danish jazz double-bassists]]\n[[Category:Male double-bassists]]\n[[Category:21st-century double-bassists]]\n[[Category:21st-century male musicians]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n\n\n{{Denmark-actor-stub}}\n{{comedian-stub}}\n", "name_user": "ArbieP", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:added * {{IMDb name|nm0141381|name=Povl Erik Carstensen}}", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Povl_Erik_Carstensen"}
{"title_page": "Pop music", "text_new": "{{About|a specific music genre|popular music in general|Popular music|other uses|Pop music (disambiguation)}}\n{{Redirect|Pop song|other uses|Pop Song (disambiguation){{!}}Pop Song}}\n{{short description|Genre of popular music which originated in its modern form in the late-90000000sderiving from rock and roll}}\n{{Infobox music genre\n| name = Pop\n| color = pink\n| bgcolor = #87CEEB\n| stylistic_origins = \n* [[Traditional pop music|Traditional pop]]<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/subgenre/traditional-pop-ma0000002961/artists  Traditional Pop, ''Allmusic.com''].  Retrieved 25 August 2016</ref>\n* [[rock and roll]]<ref name=Grove/>\n* [[Contemporary folk music|folk]]<ref name=pc1/>\n| cultural_origins = Mid-1950s,<ref name=Firth2001/> United States and United Kingdom\n| image = \n| caption = mj\n| derivatives = * [[Disco]]\n* [[New wave music|New wave]]\n| instruments = \n| subgenrelist = List of pop music genres\n| subgenres = * [[Art pop]]\n* [[Brill Building (genre)|Brill Building]]\n* [[bubblegum pop]]\n* [[dance-pop]]\n* [[experimental pop]]\n* [[hypnagogic pop]]\n* [[new wave]]\n* [[operatic pop]]\n* [[orchestral pop]]\n* [[progressive pop]]\n* [[sophisti-pop]]\n* [[space age pop]]\n* [[sunshine pop]]\n* [[synth-pop]]\n* [[teen pop]]\n* pop-ballad<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/art/pop-ballad|title=Pop ballad &#124; sentimental song|website=Encyclopedia Britannica}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/3814513|title=Genre and the Ballad|author=Seeger, Judith|year=1994|journal=Journal of Folklore Research|volume=31|issue=1/3|pages=151\u2013176|via=JSTOR}}</ref>\n| fusiongenres = * [[Baroque pop]]\n* [[Contemporary Christian music|Contemporary Christian]]\n* [[country pop]]\n* [[electropop]]\n* [[folk-pop]]\n* [[indie pop]]\n* [[jangle pop]]\n* [[Latin pop]]\n* [[noise pop]]\n* [[pop punk]]\n* [[pop-rap]]\n* [[pop rock]]\n* [[power pop]]\n* [[psychedelic pop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[reggae fusion]]\n* [[smooth jazz]]\n* [[smooth soul]]\n| regional_scenes = * [[C-pop|China]]\n* [[Indian pop|India]]\n* [[Indo pop|Indonesia]]\n* [[Cantopop|Hong Kong]]\n* [[Italian popular music#Contemporary Music|Italy]]\n* [[J-pop|Japan]]\n* [[K-pop|Korea]]\n* [[Malaysian pop|Malaysia]]\n* [[Mexican pop music|Mexico]]\n* [[Moroccan pop|Morocco]]\n* [[Pakistani pop music|Pakistan]]\n* [[P-pop|Philippines]]\n* [[Russian pop|Russia]]\n* [[Nordic popular music|Scandinavia]]\n* [[Swedish pop music|Sweden]]\n* [[Taiwanese pop|Taiwan]]\n* [[Thai pop music|Thailand]]\n* [[Turkish pop music|Turkey]]\n* [[British pop music|United Kingdom]]\n* [[American pop|United States]]\n* [[V-pop|Vietnam]]\n* [[Europop|Western Europe]]\n| local_scenes = \n| other_topics = * [[Avant-pop]]\n* [[pop music automation]]\n* [[poptimism]]\n* [[rock music]]\n| current_year = no\n}}\n'''Pop music''' is a genre of [[popular music]] that originated in its modern forms in the [[United States|US]] and the [[United Kingdom|UK]] during the mid-1950s.<ref name=Firth2001/> The terms \"popular music\" and \"pop music\" are often used interchangeably, although the former describes all music that is popular and includes many diverse styles. \"Pop\" and \"[[Rock music|rock]]\" were roughly synonymous terms until the late 1960s, when they became quite separated from each other.\n\nAlthough much of the music that appears on [[record chart]]s is seen as pop music, the genre is distinguished from chart music. Pop music often borrows elements from other styles such as [[urban contemporary|urban]], [[dance music|dance]], [[rock music|rock]], [[Latin music (genre)|Latin]], and [[country music|country]]; nevertheless, there are many key elements that define pop music. Identifying factors usually include short to medium-length songs written in a basic format (often the [[verse\u2013chorus form|verse-chorus structure]]), as well as common use of repeated choruses, melodic tunes and [[hook (music)|hooks]].\n\n==Definitions and etymology{{anchor|Etymology}}==\n[[File:The Beatles in America.JPG|thumb|left|The 1960s [[British Invasion]] marked a period when the US charts were inundated with British acts such as [[the Beatles]] (pictured 1964).]]\n\nDavid Hatch and Stephen Millward define pop music as \"a body of music which is distinguishable from popular, jazz, and folk musics\".<ref>D. Hatch and S. Millward, ''From Blues to Rock: an Analytical History of Pop Music'' (Manchester: Manchester University Press, 1987), {{ISBN|0-7190-1489-1}}, p. 1.</ref>\nAccording to [[Pete Seeger]], pop music is \"professional music which draws upon both folk music and fine arts music\".<ref name=pc1>{{Gilliland |url=https://digital.library.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metadc19745/m1/ |title=Show 1 \u2013 Play A Simple Melody: Pete Seeger on the origins of pop music}}</ref>\nAlthough pop music is seen as just the [[record chart|singles charts]], it is not the sum of all chart music. The music charts contain songs from a variety of sources, including [[classical music|classical]], [[jazz]], [[rock music|rock]], and [[novelty song]]s. As a genre, pop music is seen to exist and develop separately.<ref>R. Serge Denisoff and William L. Schurk, ''Tarnished Gold: the Record Industry Revisited'' (New Brunswick, NJ: Transaction Publishers, 3rd edn., 1986), {{ISBN|0-88738-618-0}}, pp. 2\u20133.</ref> Therefore, the term \"pop music\" may be used to describe a distinct genre, designed to appeal to all, often characterized as \"instant singles-based music aimed at teenagers\" in contrast to rock music as \"album-based music for adults\".<ref name=Firth2001/>{{refn|Musicologist Allan Moore surmises that the term \"pop music\" itself may have been popularized by [[Pop art]].<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Moore|first=Allan F.|title=Song Means: Analysing and Interpreting Recorded Popular Song|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S6DeCwAAQBAJ|year=2016|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-05265-4}}</ref>}}\n\nPop music continuously evolves along with the term's definition. According to music writer Bill Lamb, popular music is defined as \"the music since industrialization in the 1800s that is most in line with the tastes and interests of the urban middle class.\"<ref name=\"What Is Pop Music\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.thoughtco.com/what-is-pop-music-3246980|title=What Is Pop Music?|access-date=|last = Lamb |first =Bill|website = ThoughtCo.|date = 29 September 2018 }}</ref> The term \"pop song\" was first used in 1926, in the sense of a piece of music \"having popular appeal\".<ref name=OED>J. Simpson and E. Weiner, ''Oxford English Dictionary''(Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1989). {{ISBN|0-19-861186-2}}, cf. pop.</ref> Hatch and Millward indicate that many events in the history of recording in the 1920s can be seen as the birth of the modern pop music industry, including in [[country music|country]], [[blues]], and [[hillbilly music]].<ref>D. Hatch and S. Millward, ''From Blues to Rock: an Analytical History of Pop Music'', {{ISBN|0-7190-1489-1}}, p. 49.</ref>\n\n[[File: Rolling stones - 11 luglio 2006 - san siro.jpg|thumb|right|''The Oxford Dictionary of Music'' states that the term \"pop\" refers to music performed by such artists as  [[the Rolling Stones]] (pictured here in a 2006 performance).]]\n\nAccording to the website of ''[[The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians]]'', the term \"pop music\" \"originated in [[United Kingdom|Britain]] in the mid-1950s as a description for [[rock and roll]] and the new youth music styles that it influenced\".<ref name=Grove>R. Middleton, et al., [http://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/public/book/omo_gmo \"Pop\"], ''Grove music online'', retrieved 14 March 2010. {{Subscription required}}</ref> ''The Oxford Dictionary of Music'' states that while pop's \"earlier meaning meant concerts appealing to a wide audience [...] since the late 1950s, however, pop has had the special meaning of non-classical mus[ic], usually in the form of songs, performed by such artists as [[The Beatles]], [[The Rolling Stones]], [[ABBA]], etc.\"<ref>\"Pop\", [http://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/public/book/omo_t237 ''The Oxford Dictionary of Music''], retrieved 9 March 2010.{{Subscription required}}</ref> ''Grove Music Online'' also states that \"[...] in the early 1960s, [the term] 'pop music' competed terminologically with [[beat music]] [in England], while in the US its coverage overlapped (as it still does) with that of 'rock and roll'\".<ref name=Grove/>\n\nFrom about 1967, the term \u201cpop music\u201d was increasingly used in opposition to the term [[rock music]], a division that gave generic significance to both terms.<ref name=Gloag983>Kenneth Gloag in ''The Oxford Companion to Music'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2001), {{ISBN|0-19-866212-2}}, p. 983.</ref> While rock aspired to [[authenticity (philosophy)|authenticity]] and an expansion of the possibilities of popular music,<ref name=Gloag983/> pop was more commercial, ephemeral, and accessible.<ref name=Warner2003>T. Warner, ''Pop Music: Technology and Creativity: Trevor Horn and the Digital Revolution'' (Aldershot: Ashgate, 2003), {{ISBN|0-7546-3132-X}}, pp.&nbsp;3\u20134.</ref> According to British musicologist [[Simon Frith]], pop music is produced \"as a matter of [[business|enterprise]] not art\", and is \"designed to appeal to everyone\" but \"doesn't come from any particular place or mark off any particular taste\". Frith adds that it is \"not driven by any significant ambition except profit and commercial reward [...] and, in musical terms, it is essentially conservative\". It is, \"provided from on high (by record companies, radio programmers, and concert promoters) rather than being made from below&nbsp;... Pop is not a [[DIY|do-it-yourself]] music but is professionally produced and packaged\".<ref name=\"Firth2001\"/> {{clear}}\n\n==Characteristics==\n[[File:Elvis_Presley_-_TV_Radio_Mirror,_March_1957_01.jpg|thumb|left|250px|[[Elvis Presley]]]]\n\n{{listen\n | filename    = Righteous Brothers - You've Lost That Lovin' Feelin'.ogg\n | title       = The Righteous Brothers \u2013 \"You've Lost That Lovin' Feelin'\" (1965)\n | pos         = right\n | description ={{As of|2011}}, \"[[You've Lost That Lovin' Feelin']]\" ranks as the most frequently played song in US radio history.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-15186967 |title=Van's Brown Eyed Girl hits the 10 million mark in US|date=5 October 2011 |work=BBC }}</ref> It is described by music writers [[Nick Logan]] and [[Bob Woffinden]] as \"the ultimate pop record\".<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QWBPAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA101#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Encyclopedia of Great Popular Song Recordings, Volume 2|author=Steve Sullivan|pages=101\u2013103 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |year=2013 |isbn= 978-0-8108-8296-6 }}</ref>\n}}\n\nAccording to Frith, characteristics of pop music include an aim of appealing to a general audience, rather than to a particular sub-culture or ideology, and an emphasis on craftsmanship rather than formal \"artistic\" qualities.<ref name=Firth2001/> Music scholar Timothy Warner said it typically has an emphasis on recording, production, and technology, rather than live performance; a tendency to reflect existing trends rather than [[progressive music|progressive developments]]; and aims to encourage dancing or uses dance-oriented rhythms.<ref name=Warner2003/>\n\nThe main medium of pop music is the song, often between two and a half and three and a half minutes in length, generally marked by a consistent and noticeable [[rhythm|rhythmic element]], a mainstream style and a simple traditional [[song structure (popular music)|structure]].<ref>W. Everett, ''Expression in Pop-rock Music: A Collection of Critical and Analytical Essays'' (London: Taylor & Francis, 2000), p. 272.</ref> Common variants include the verse-chorus form and the [[thirty-two-bar form]], with a focus on [[melody|melodies]] and catchy [[hook (music)|hooks]], and a [[refrain|chorus]] that contrasts melodically, rhythmically and [[harmony|harmonically]] with the [[Verse (music)|verse]].<ref>J. Shepherd, ''Continuum Encyclopedia of Popular Music of the World: Performance and production'' (Continuum, 2003), p. 508.</ref> The beat and the melodies tend to be simple, with limited harmonic accompaniment.<ref>V. Kramarz, ''The Pop Formulas: Harmonic Tools of the Hit Makers'' (Mel Bay Publications, 2007), p. 61.</ref> The lyrics of modern pop songs typically focus on simple themes&nbsp;\u2013 often love and romantic relationships&nbsp;\u2013 although there are notable exceptions.<ref name=Firth2001/>\n\n[[Harmony (music)|Harmony]] and [[chord progression]]s in pop music are often \"that of [[Classical music|classical]] European [[tonality]], only more simple-minded.\"<ref>Winkler, Peter (1978). \"Toward a theory of pop harmony\", ''In Theory Only'', 4, pp.&nbsp;3\u201326.</ref> Clich\u00e9s include the [[close and open harmony|barbershop quartet-style harmony]] (i.e. ii \u2013 V \u2013 I) and [[blues scale]]-influenced harmony.<ref>Sargeant, p. 198. cited in Winkler (1978), p. 4.</ref> There was a lessening of the influence of traditional views of the [[circle of fifths]] between the mid-1950s and the late 1970s, including less predominance for the [[dominant (music)|dominant]] [[diatonic function|function]].<ref>Winkler (1978), p. 22.</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Development and influence==\n\n===Technology and media===\n\n{{multiple image\n| total_width = 230\n| align = right\n| image1 = Michael Jackson in 1988.jpg\n| width1 = \n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Madonna, Rotterdam, 26-8-1987.jpg\n| width2 = \n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer = [[Michael Jackson]] (left) and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] (right), known respectively as the \"[[Honorific nicknames in popular music|King and Queen of Pop]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2008/oct/28/madonna-pop-art|first=Alan|last=McGee|authorlink=Alan McGee|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=August 20, 2008|accessdate=April 17, 2013|title=Madonna Pop Art}}</ref>\n| direction = \n}}\n\nIn the 1940s improved [[microphone]] design allowed a more intimate singing style and ten or twenty years later, inexpensive and more durable 45 rpm records for singles \"revolutionized the manner in which pop has been disseminated\", which helped to move pop music to \"a record/radio/film star system\".<ref name=Buckley>D. Buckley, \"Pop\" \"II. Implications of technology\", ''Grove Music Online'', retrieved 15 March 2010.</ref> Another technological change was the widespread availability of television in the 1950s; with televised performances, \"pop stars had to have a visual presence\".<ref name=Buckley/> In the 1960s, the introduction of inexpensive, portable [[transistor radio]]s meant that teenagers in the developed world could listen to music outside of the home.<ref name=Buckley/> By the early 1980s, the promotion of pop music had been greatly affected by the rise of music television channels like [[MTV]], which \"favoured those artists such as [[Michael Jackson]] and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] who had a strong visual appeal\".<ref name=Buckley/>\n\n[[Multi-track recording]] (from the 1960s); and [[sampling (music)|digital sampling]] (from the 1980s) have also been utilized as methods for the creation and elaboration of pop music.<ref name=Firth2001/> During the mid-1960s, pop music made repeated forays into new sounds, styles, and techniques that inspired public discourse among its listeners. The word \"progressive\" was frequently used, and it was thought that every song and single was to be a \"progression\" from the last.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hewitt|first1=Paolo|last2=Hellier|first2=John|title=Steve Marriott: All Too Beautiful|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CxhzCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT162|year=2015|publisher=Dean Street Press|isbn=978-1-910570-69-2|page=162}}</ref> [[Music journalism|Music critic]] [[Simon Reynolds]] writes that beginning with 1967, a divide would exist between \"progressive\" pop and \"mass/chart\" pop, a separation which was \"also, broadly, one between boys and girls, middle-class and working-class.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Reynolds|first=Simon|authorlink=Simon Reynolds|title=On Record: Rock, Pop and the Written Word|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lauJAgAAQBAJ|year=2006|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-93951-0|chapter=New Pop and its Aftermath|page=398}}</ref>\n\nThe latter half of the 20th-century included a large-scale trend in American culture in which the boundaries between art and pop music were increasingly blurred.<ref>{{cite book|pp=317, 1233|editor-last=Edmondson|editor-first=Jacqueline|title=Music in American Life: An Encyclopedia of the Songs, Styles, Stars, and Stories that Shaped our Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TQPXAQAAQBAJ|year=2013|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-39348-8}}</ref> Between 1950 and 1970, there was a debate of pop versus art.<ref name=\"PMLoss2015\"/> Since then, certain music publications have embraced the music's legitimacy, a trend referred to as \"[[poptimism]]\".<ref name=\"PMLoss2015\">{{cite web|last1=Loss|first1=Robert|title=No Apologies: A Critique of the Rockist v. Poptimist Paradigm|url=http://www.popmatters.com/column/196122-no-apologies-a-critique-of-the-rockist-v.-poptimist-paradigm/|website=[[PopMatters]]|date=August 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Stylistic evolution===\n[[File:Katy_Perry_2011.jpg|thumb|left|[[Katy Perry]]'s characteristic spinning peppermint swirl dress which she wore during the California Dreams tour|alt=]]\n\nThroughout its development, pop music has absorbed influences from other genres of popular music. Early pop music drew on the [[sentimental ballad]] for its form, gained its use of vocal harmonies from [[gospel music|gospel]] and [[soul music]], instrumentation from [[jazz]] and [[rock music]], orchestration from [[classical music]], tempo from [[dance music]], backing from [[electronic music]], rhythmic elements from [[hip-hop music]], and spoken passages from [[rap music|rap]].<ref name=Firth2001>S. Frith, W. Straw, and J. Street, eds, ''[[Cambridge Companions to Music|The Cambridge Companion to Pop and Rock]]'' (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press), {{ISBN|0-521-55660-0}}, pp.&nbsp;95\u2013105.</ref>{{verification needed|date=February 2017}} In 2016, a ''[[Scientific Reports]]'' study that examined over 464,000 recordings of popular music recorded between 1955 and 2010 found that since the 1960s, pop music had found less variety in pitch progressions, grown average loudness levels,<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1038/srep00521|pmid=22837813|pmc=3405292|title=Measuring the Evolution of Contemporary Western Popular Music|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=2|pages=521|year=2012|last1=Serr\u00e0|first1=Joan|last2=Corral|first2=\u00c1lvaro|last3=Bogu\u00f1\u00e1|first3=Mari\u00e1n|last4=Haro|first4=Mart\u00edn|last5=Arcos|first5=Josep Ll.}}</ref> less diverse instrumentation and recording techniques, and less timbral variety.<ref name=\"Matson\"/> ''[[Scientific American]]''{{'}}s John Matson reported that this \"seems to support the popular anecdotal observation that pop music of yore was \"better\", or at least more varied, than today's top-40 stuff\". However, he also noted that the study may not have been entirely representative of pop in each generation.<ref name=\"Matson\">[http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/observations/is-pop-music-evolving-or-is-it-just-getting-louder/ John Matson, \"Is Pop Music Evolving, or Is It Just Getting Louder?\", ''Scientific American'', 26 July 2012]. Retrieved 30 March 2016</ref>\n\nIn the 1960s, the majority of mainstream pop music fell in two categories: guitar, drum and bass groups or singers backed by a traditional orchestra.<ref>{{cite web|title=Making Arrangements\u2014A Rough Guide To Song Construction & Arrangement, Part 1 |url=http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/1997_articles/oct97/arranging1.html |work=Sound on Sound |accessdate=8 May 2014 |date=October 1997 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140508082609/http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/1997_articles/oct97/arranging1.html |archivedate=8 May 2014 |df= }}</ref> Since early in the decade, it was common for pop producers, songwriters, and engineers to freely experiment with musical form, [[orchestration]], [[reverberation|unnatural reverb]], and other sound effects. Some of the best known examples are [[Phil Spector]]'s [[Wall of Sound]] and [[Joe Meek]]'s use of homemade electronic sound effects for acts like [[the Tornados]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Blake|first=Andrew|editor-last1=Cook|editor-first1=Nicholas|editor-last2=Clarke|editor-first2=Eric|editor-last3=Leech-Wilkinson|editor-first3=Daniel|title=The Cambridge Companion to Recorded Music|chapter=Recording practices and the role of the producer|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xb0hAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA45|date=2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-82796-6|page=45}}</ref> At the same time, pop music on radio and in both American and British film moved away from refined [[Tin Pan Alley]] to more eccentric songwriting and incorporated reverb-drenched rock guitar, symphonic strings, and horns played by groups of properly arranged and rehearsed studio musicians.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pareles|first=Jon|authorlink=Jon Pareles|date=October 31, 2008|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/01/arts/music/01pupp.html?_r=0|title=Orchestral Pop, the Way It Was (More or Less)|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=July 4, 2013}}</ref>  A 2019 study held by [[New York University]] in which 643 participants had to rank how familiar a pop song is to them, songs from the 1960s turned out to be the most memorable, significantly more than songs from recent years 2000 to 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smoothradio.com/news/music/best-decade-pop-music/|title=The greatest decade for pop music has been revealed (according to science)|website=Smooth|language=en|access-date=2019-03-31}}</ref>\n\nBefore the [[progressive pop]] of the late 1960s, performers were typically unable to decide on the artistic content of their music.<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Willis|first=Paul E.|authorlink=Paul Willis|title=Profane Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y7oWBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA219|year=2014|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-6514-7|page=217}}</ref> Assisted by the mid-1960s economic boom, record labels began investing in artists, giving them the freedom to experiment, and offering them limited control over their content and marketing.{{sfn|Moore|2016|p=202}} This situation declined after the late 1970s and would not reemerge until the rise of [[Internet]] stars.{{sfn|Moore|2016|p=202}} [[Indie pop]], which developed in the late 1970s, marked another departure from the glamour of contemporary pop music, with guitar bands formed on the then-novel premise that one could record and release their own music without having to procure a [[record contract]] from a major label.<ref>{{Citation|title=Twee as Fuck: The Story of Indie Pop |first=Nitsuh |last=Abebe |work=Pitchfork Media |date=24 October 2005 |url=http://pitchfork.com/features/articles/6176-twee-as-fuck/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5wjlLnVho?url=http://pitchfork.com/features/articles/6176-twee-as-fuck/ |archivedate=24 February 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n\n[[Latin pop]] rose in popularity in the [[United States]] during the 1950s with early rock and roll success [[Ritchie Valens]], though it truly rose to prominence during the 1970s and 1980s with the likes of [[Los Lobos]].<ref name=\"Portwood Portwood 2019\">{{cite web | last=Portwood | first=Jerry | last2=Portwood | first2=Jerry | title=Ritchie Valens Musical in the Works From Los Lobos' Louie Perez and David Hidalgo | website=Rolling Stone | date=December 12, 2019 | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/ritchie-valens-musical-los-lobos-925326/ | access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref> With later [[Hispanic and Latino Americans]] seeing success within pop music charts, 1990s pop successes stayed popular in both their original genres and in broader pop music. Artists like [[Selena]] saw large-scale pop music presence, and crossover appeal with fans of [[Tejano music]] trailblazers like [[Lydia Mendoza]]; likewise in other genres like [[Lorenzo Antonio]] and [[Sparx (US band)|Sparx]], who are recognized throughout [[Latin America]] as well as within their [[New Mexico music]] repertoire of [[Al Hurricane]] and [[Antonia Apodaca]].<ref>{{cite book | last=Aldama | first=A.J. | last2=Sandoval | first2=C. | last3=Garc\u00eda | first3=P.J. | title=Performing the US Latina and Latino Borderlands | publisher=Indiana University Press | year=2012 | isbn=978-0-253-00295-2 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a7KXaqig1YwC&pg=PA224 | access-date=February 14, 2020 | page=224}}</ref> Musicians like [[Shakira]], [[Ricky Martin]], [[Selena Gomez]], and [[Demi Lovato]] seen lasting mass-appeal within pop music circles. Latin pop hit singles, like \u201c[[Macarena]]\u201d by [[Los del R\u00edo]] and \u201c[[Despacito]]\u201d by [[Luis Fonsi]] have seen record-breaking success on worldwide pop music charts.<ref name=\"Villafa\u00f1e 2017\">{{cite web | last=Villafa\u00f1e | first=Veronica | title=Still No.1, Record-Breaking 'Despacito' Ties 'Macarena' Streak On Hot 100, But Is Snubbed By MTV | website=Forbes | date=August 14, 2017 | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/veronicavillafane/2017/08/14/still-no-1-record-breaking-despacito-ties-macarena-streak-on-hot-100-but-is-snubbed-by-mtv/ | access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe 1980s are commonly remembered for an increase in the use of [[digital recording]], associated with the usage of [[synthesizer]]s, with [[synth-pop]] music and other [[electronic music|electronic]] genres featuring non-traditional instruments increasing in popularity.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/08/29/arts/rap-music-brash-and-swaggering-enters-mainstream.html | work=The New York Times | first=Glenn | last=Collins | title=Rap Music, Brash And Swaggering, Enters Mainstream | date=1988-08-29}}</ref> By 2014, pop music worldwide had been permeated by [[electronic dance music]].<ref name=\"Christgau\"/> In 2018, researchers at the [[University of California, Irvine]], concluded that pop music has become 'sadder' since the 1980s. The elements of [[happiness]] and brightness have eventually been replaced with the electronic beats making the pop music more 'sad yet danceable'.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thefader.com/2018/05/16/sadness-in-pop-music-study|title=New study finds pop music has gotten extremely depressing but also more fun to dance to|work=The FADER|access-date=2018-05-21|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===International spread===\n{{Quote box\n |quote = The story of pop music is largely the story of the intertwining pop culture of the United States and the United Kingdom in the postwar era.\n |source =&nbsp;\u2014 [[Bob Stanley (musician)|Bob Stanley]]<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite web|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|year=2014|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/bn/bn2014-07.php|title=Anti-Rockism's Hall of Fame|work=[[The Barnes & Noble Review]]|accessdate=August 18, 2015}}</ref>\n |quoted = true\n |bgcolor =\n |width = 22%\n |salign = right\n |align = right\n |border = 1px\n |fontsize = 89%\n}}\n\nPop music has been dominated by the American and (from the mid-1960s) British [[music industry|music industries]], whose influence has made pop music something of an international monoculture, but most regions and countries have their own form of pop music, sometimes producing local versions of wider trends, and lending them local characteristics.<ref>J. Kun, ''Audiotopia: Music, Race, and America'' (Berkeley, CA: University of California Press, 2005), {{ISBN|0-520-24424-9}}, p. 201.</ref> Some of these trends (for example [[Europop]]) have had a significant impact of the development of the genre.<ref name=Firth2002>\"Star profiles\" in S. Frith, W. Stray and J. Street, ''The Cambridge Companion to Pop and Rock'' (Cambridge University Press, 2001), {{ISBN|0-521-55660-0}}, pp. 199\u2013200.</ref>\n\nAccording to ''Grove Music Online'', \"Western-derived pop styles, whether coexisting with or marginalizing distinctively local genres, have spread throughout the world and have come to constitute stylistic common denominators in global commercial music cultures\".<ref name=PManuel>P. Manuel, \"Pop. Non-Western cultures 1. Global dissemination\", ''Grove Music Online'', retrieved 14 March 2010.</ref> Some non-Western countries, such as Japan, have developed a thriving pop music industry, most of which is devoted to Western-style pop. Japan has for several years produced a greater quantity of music than everywhere except the US.{{Clarify|reason=vague|date=April 2017}}<ref name=PManuel/> The spread of Western-style pop music has been interpreted variously as representing processes of Americanization, [[Radio Homogenization|homogenization]], modernization, creative appropriation, [[cultural imperialism]], or a more general process of [[globalization]].<ref name=PManuel/>\n\nIn Korea, pop music's influence has led to the birth of [[boy bands]] and [[girl groups]] which have gained overseas renown through both their music and aesthetics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.es/yodona/2015/12/03/565f220b46163ff4308b45c9.html|title=K-Pop, la m\u00fasica y la moda 'rarita' coreana que arrasa la red|date=December 3, 2015|website=ELMUNDO}}</ref> Korean [[co-ed groups]] (mixed gender groups) have not been as successful.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/blog/2016/08/25/why-arent-there-many-mixed-gender-k-pop-groups|title=Why aren't there many mixed gender K-pop groups?|website=SBS PopAsia}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Pop music|Music}}\n* [[Honorific nicknames in popular music]]\n* [[Origins of rock and roll]]\n* [[Popular music pedagogy]]\n* [[List of popular music genres]]\n* [[History of music]]\n* [[Public domain music]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n{{refbegin}}\n* [[Theodor W. Adorno|Adorno, Theodor W.]], (1942) \"On Popular Music\", Institute of Social Research.\n* Bell, John L., (2000) ''The Singing Thing: A Case for Congregational Song'', GIA Publications, {{ISBN|1-57999-100-9}}\n* Bindas, Kenneth J., (1992) ''America's Musical Pulse: Popular Music in Twentieth-Century Society'', Praeger.\n* [[Donald Clarke (writer)|Clarke, Donald]], (1995) ''The Rise and Fall of Popular Music'', St Martin's Press. [https://web.archive.org/web/20071231045026/http://www.musicweb.uk.net/RiseandFall/index.htm ]\n* Dolfsma, Wilfred, (1999) ''Valuing Pop Music: Institutions, Values and Economics'', Eburon.\n* Dolfsma, Wilfred, (2004) ''Institutional Economics and the Formation of Preferences: The Advent of Pop Music'', Edward Elgar Publishing.\n* [[Simon Frith|Frith, Simon]], Straw, Will, Street, John, eds, (2001), ''The Cambridge Companion to Pop and Rock'', Cambridge University Press,\n* [[Simon Frith|Frith, Simon]] (2004) ''Popular Music: Critical Concepts in Media and Cultural Studies'', Routledge.\n* [[Charlie Gillett|Gillett, Charlie]], (1970) ''The Sound of the City. The Rise of Rock and Roll'', Outerbridge & Dienstfrey.\n* Hatch, David and Stephen Millward, (1987), ''From Blues to Rock: an Analytical History of Pop Music'', Manchester University Press, {{ISBN|0-7190-1489-1}}\n* Johnson, Julian, (2002) ''Who Needs Classical Music?: Cultural Choice and Musical Value'', Oxford University Press, {{ISBN|0-19-514681-6}}.\n* [[Jeff Kent (author)|Kent, Jeff]], (1983) ''The Rise and Fall of Rock'', Witan Books, {{ISBN|0-9508981-0-4}}.\n* Lonergan, David F., (2004) ''Hit Records, 1950\u20131975'', Scarecrow Press, {{ISBN|0-8108-5129-6}}.\n* Maultsby, Portia K., (7907) ''Intra- and International Identities in American Popular Music'', Trading Culture.\n* [[Richard Middleton (musicologist)|Middleton, Richard]], (1990) ''Studying Popular Music'', Open University Press.\n* Negus, Bob, (1999) ''Music Genres and Corporate Cultures'', Routledge, {{ISBN|0-415-17399-X}}.\n* [[Henry Pleasants (music critic)|Pleasants, Henry]] (1969) ''Serious Music and All That Jazz'', Simon & Schuster.\n* [[Lillian Roxon|Roxon, Lillian]], (1969) ''Rock Encyclopedia'', Grosset & Dunlap.\n* Shuker, Roy, (2002) ''Popular Music: The Key Concepts'', Routledge, (2nd edn.) {{ISBN|0-415-28425-2}}.\n* Starr, Larry & Waterman, Christopher, (2002) ''American Popular Music: From Minstrelsy to MTV'', Oxford University Press.\n* Watkins, S. Craig, (2005) ''Hip Hop Matters: Politics, Pop Culture, and the Struggle for the Soul of a Movement'', Beacon Press, {{ISBN|0-8070-0982-2}}.\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Pop music}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170407053620/http://musiclife.mobi/filelist/1017/sabrang_%282017%29_mp3/new2old/1 The Consumption of Music and the Expression of Values: A Social Economic Explanation for the Advent of Pop Music], Wilfred Dolfsma, ''[[American Journal of Economics and Sociology]]'', October 1999.\n\n{{Pop music}}\n{{Media culture}}\n{{Western world}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pop Music}}\n[[Category:Pop music| ]]\n[[Category:Western culture]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 1920s]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|a specific music genre|popular music in general|Popular music|other uses|Pop music (disambiguation)}}\n{{Redirect|Pop song|other uses|Pop Song (disambiguation){{!}}Pop Song}}\n{{short description|Genre of popular music which originated in its modern form in the late-1950s deriving from rock and roll}}\n{{Infobox music genre\n| name = Pop\n| color = pink\n| bgcolor = #87CEEB\n| stylistic_origins = \n* [[Traditional pop music|Traditional pop]]<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/subgenre/traditional-pop-ma0000002961/artists  Traditional Pop, ''Allmusic.com''].  Retrieved 25 August 2016</ref>\n* [[rock and roll]]<ref name=Grove/>\n* [[Contemporary folk music|folk]]<ref name=pc1/>\n| cultural_origins = Mid-1950s,<ref name=Firth2001/> United States and United Kingdom\n| image = \n| caption = mj\n| derivatives = * [[Disco]]\n* [[New wave music|New wave]]\n| instruments = \n| subgenrelist = List of pop music genres\n| subgenres = * [[Art pop]]\n* [[Brill Building (genre)|Brill Building]]\n* [[bubblegum pop]]\n* [[dance-pop]]\n* [[experimental pop]]\n* [[hypnagogic pop]]\n* [[new wave]]\n* [[operatic pop]]\n* [[orchestral pop]]\n* [[progressive pop]]\n* [[sophisti-pop]]\n* [[space age pop]]\n* [[sunshine pop]]\n* [[synth-pop]]\n* [[teen pop]]\n* pop-ballad<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/art/pop-ballad|title=Pop ballad &#124; sentimental song|website=Encyclopedia Britannica}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/3814513|title=Genre and the Ballad|author=Seeger, Judith|year=1994|journal=Journal of Folklore Research|volume=31|issue=1/3|pages=151\u2013176|via=JSTOR}}</ref>\n| fusiongenres = * [[Baroque pop]]\n* [[Contemporary Christian music|Contemporary Christian]]\n* [[country pop]]\n* [[electropop]]\n* [[folk-pop]]\n* [[indie pop]]\n* [[jangle pop]]\n* [[Latin pop]]\n* [[noise pop]]\n* [[pop punk]]\n* [[pop-rap]]\n* [[pop rock]]\n* [[power pop]]\n* [[psychedelic pop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[reggae fusion]]\n* [[smooth jazz]]\n* [[smooth soul]]\n| regional_scenes = * [[C-pop|China]]\n* [[Indian pop|India]]\n* [[Indo pop|Indonesia]]\n* [[Cantopop|Hong Kong]]\n* [[Italian popular music#Contemporary Music|Italy]]\n* [[J-pop|Japan]]\n* [[K-pop|Korea]]\n* [[Malaysian pop|Malaysia]]\n* [[Mexican pop music|Mexico]]\n* [[Moroccan pop|Morocco]]\n* [[Pakistani pop music|Pakistan]]\n* [[P-pop|Philippines]]\n* [[Russian pop|Russia]]\n* [[Nordic popular music|Scandinavia]]\n* [[Swedish pop music|Sweden]]\n* [[Taiwanese pop|Taiwan]]\n* [[Thai pop music|Thailand]]\n* [[Turkish pop music|Turkey]]\n* [[British pop music|United Kingdom]]\n* [[American pop|United States]]\n* [[V-pop|Vietnam]]\n* [[Europop|Western Europe]]\n| local_scenes = \n| other_topics = * [[Avant-pop]]\n* [[pop music automation]]\n* [[poptimism]]\n* [[rock music]]\n| current_year = no\n}}\n'''Pop music''' is a genre of [[popular music]] that originated in its modern forms in the [[United States|US]] and the [[United Kingdom|UK]] during the mid-1950s.<ref name=Firth2001/> The terms \"popular music\" and \"pop music\" are often used interchangeably, although the former describes all music that is popular and includes many diverse styles. \"Pop\" and \"[[Rock music|rock]]\" were roughly synonymous terms until the late 1960s, when they became quite separated from each other.\n\nAlthough much of the music that appears on [[record chart]]s is seen as pop music, the genre is distinguished from chart music. Pop music often borrows elements from other styles such as [[urban contemporary|urban]], [[dance music|dance]], [[rock music|rock]], [[Latin music (genre)|Latin]], and [[country music|country]]; nevertheless, there are many key elements that define pop music. Identifying factors usually include short to medium-length songs written in a basic format (often the [[verse\u2013chorus form|verse-chorus structure]]), as well as common use of repeated choruses, melodic tunes and [[hook (music)|hooks]].\n\n==Definitions and etymology{{anchor|Etymology}}==\n[[File:The Beatles in America.JPG|thumb|left|The 1960s [[British Invasion]] marked a period when the US charts were inundated with British acts such as [[the Beatles]] (pictured 1964).]]\n\nDavid Hatch and Stephen Millward define pop music as \"a body of music which is distinguishable from popular, jazz, and folk musics\".<ref>D. Hatch and S. Millward, ''From Blues to Rock: an Analytical History of Pop Music'' (Manchester: Manchester University Press, 1987), {{ISBN|0-7190-1489-1}}, p. 1.</ref>\nAccording to [[Pete Seeger]], pop music is \"professional music which draws upon both folk music and fine arts music\".<ref name=pc1>{{Gilliland |url=https://digital.library.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metadc19745/m1/ |title=Show 1 \u2013 Play A Simple Melody: Pete Seeger on the origins of pop music}}</ref>\nAlthough pop music is seen as just the [[record chart|singles charts]], it is not the sum of all chart music. The music charts contain songs from a variety of sources, including [[classical music|classical]], [[jazz]], [[rock music|rock]], and [[novelty song]]s. As a genre, pop music is seen to exist and develop separately.<ref>R. Serge Denisoff and William L. Schurk, ''Tarnished Gold: the Record Industry Revisited'' (New Brunswick, NJ: Transaction Publishers, 3rd edn., 1986), {{ISBN|0-88738-618-0}}, pp. 2\u20133.</ref> Therefore, the term \"pop music\" may be used to describe a distinct genre, designed to appeal to all, often characterized as \"instant singles-based music aimed at teenagers\" in contrast to rock music as \"album-based music for adults\".<ref name=Firth2001/>{{refn|Musicologist Allan Moore surmises that the term \"pop music\" itself may have been popularized by [[Pop art]].<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Moore|first=Allan F.|title=Song Means: Analysing and Interpreting Recorded Popular Song|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S6DeCwAAQBAJ|year=2016|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-05265-4}}</ref>}}\n\nPop music continuously evolves along with the term's definition. According to music writer Bill Lamb, popular music is defined as \"the music since industrialization in the 1800s that is most in line with the tastes and interests of the urban middle class.\"<ref name=\"What Is Pop Music\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.thoughtco.com/what-is-pop-music-3246980|title=What Is Pop Music?|access-date=|last = Lamb |first =Bill|website = ThoughtCo.|date = 29 September 2018 }}</ref> The term \"pop song\" was first used in 1926, in the sense of a piece of music \"having popular appeal\".<ref name=OED>J. Simpson and E. Weiner, ''Oxford English Dictionary''(Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1989). {{ISBN|0-19-861186-2}}, cf. pop.</ref> Hatch and Millward indicate that many events in the history of recording in the 1920s can be seen as the birth of the modern pop music industry, including in [[country music|country]], [[blues]], and [[hillbilly music]].<ref>D. Hatch and S. Millward, ''From Blues to Rock: an Analytical History of Pop Music'', {{ISBN|0-7190-1489-1}}, p. 49.</ref>\n\n[[File: Rolling stones - 11 luglio 2006 - san siro.jpg|thumb|right|''The Oxford Dictionary of Music'' states that the term \"pop\" refers to music performed by such artists as  [[the Rolling Stones]] (pictured here in a 2006 performance).]]\n\nAccording to the website of ''[[The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians]]'', the term \"pop music\" \"originated in [[United Kingdom|Britain]] in the mid-1950s as a description for [[rock and roll]] and the new youth music styles that it influenced\".<ref name=Grove>R. Middleton, et al., [http://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/public/book/omo_gmo \"Pop\"], ''Grove music online'', retrieved 14 March 2010. {{Subscription required}}</ref> ''The Oxford Dictionary of Music'' states that while pop's \"earlier meaning meant concerts appealing to a wide audience [...] since the late 1950s, however, pop has had the special meaning of non-classical mus[ic], usually in the form of songs, performed by such artists as [[The Beatles]], [[The Rolling Stones]], [[ABBA]], etc.\"<ref>\"Pop\", [http://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/public/book/omo_t237 ''The Oxford Dictionary of Music''], retrieved 9 March 2010.{{Subscription required}}</ref> ''Grove Music Online'' also states that \"[...] in the early 1960s, [the term] 'pop music' competed terminologically with [[beat music]] [in England], while in the US its coverage overlapped (as it still does) with that of 'rock and roll'\".<ref name=Grove/>\n\nFrom about 1967, the term \u201cpop music\u201d was increasingly used in opposition to the term [[rock music]], a division that gave generic significance to both terms.<ref name=Gloag983>Kenneth Gloag in ''The Oxford Companion to Music'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2001), {{ISBN|0-19-866212-2}}, p. 983.</ref> While rock aspired to [[authenticity (philosophy)|authenticity]] and an expansion of the possibilities of popular music,<ref name=Gloag983/> pop was more commercial, ephemeral, and accessible.<ref name=Warner2003>T. Warner, ''Pop Music: Technology and Creativity: Trevor Horn and the Digital Revolution'' (Aldershot: Ashgate, 2003), {{ISBN|0-7546-3132-X}}, pp.&nbsp;3\u20134.</ref> According to British musicologist [[Simon Frith]], pop music is produced \"as a matter of [[business|enterprise]] not art\", and is \"designed to appeal to everyone\" but \"doesn't come from any particular place or mark off any particular taste\". Frith adds that it is \"not driven by any significant ambition except profit and commercial reward [...] and, in musical terms, it is essentially conservative\". It is, \"provided from on high (by record companies, radio programmers, and concert promoters) rather than being made from below&nbsp;... Pop is not a [[DIY|do-it-yourself]] music but is professionally produced and packaged\".<ref name=\"Firth2001\"/> {{clear}}\n\n==Characteristics==\n[[File:Elvis_Presley_-_TV_Radio_Mirror,_March_1957_01.jpg|thumb|left|250px|[[Elvis Presley]]]]\n\n{{listen\n | filename    = Righteous Brothers - You've Lost That Lovin' Feelin'.ogg\n | title       = The Righteous Brothers \u2013 \"You've Lost That Lovin' Feelin'\" (1965)\n | pos         = right\n | description ={{As of|2011}}, \"[[You've Lost That Lovin' Feelin']]\" ranks as the most frequently played song in US radio history.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-15186967 |title=Van's Brown Eyed Girl hits the 10 million mark in US|date=5 October 2011 |work=BBC }}</ref> It is described by music writers [[Nick Logan]] and [[Bob Woffinden]] as \"the ultimate pop record\".<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QWBPAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA101#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Encyclopedia of Great Popular Song Recordings, Volume 2|author=Steve Sullivan|pages=101\u2013103 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |year=2013 |isbn= 978-0-8108-8296-6 }}</ref>\n}}\n\nAccording to Frith, characteristics of pop music include an aim of appealing to a general audience, rather than to a particular sub-culture or ideology, and an emphasis on craftsmanship rather than formal \"artistic\" qualities.<ref name=Firth2001/> Music scholar Timothy Warner said it typically has an emphasis on recording, production, and technology, rather than live performance; a tendency to reflect existing trends rather than [[progressive music|progressive developments]]; and aims to encourage dancing or uses dance-oriented rhythms.<ref name=Warner2003/>\n\nThe main medium of pop music is the song, often between two and a half and three and a half minutes in length, generally marked by a consistent and noticeable [[rhythm|rhythmic element]], a mainstream style and a simple traditional [[song structure (popular music)|structure]].<ref>W. Everett, ''Expression in Pop-rock Music: A Collection of Critical and Analytical Essays'' (London: Taylor & Francis, 2000), p. 272.</ref> Common variants include the verse-chorus form and the [[thirty-two-bar form]], with a focus on [[melody|melodies]] and catchy [[hook (music)|hooks]], and a [[refrain|chorus]] that contrasts melodically, rhythmically and [[harmony|harmonically]] with the [[Verse (music)|verse]].<ref>J. Shepherd, ''Continuum Encyclopedia of Popular Music of the World: Performance and production'' (Continuum, 2003), p. 508.</ref> The beat and the melodies tend to be simple, with limited harmonic accompaniment.<ref>V. Kramarz, ''The Pop Formulas: Harmonic Tools of the Hit Makers'' (Mel Bay Publications, 2007), p. 61.</ref> The lyrics of modern pop songs typically focus on simple themes&nbsp;\u2013 often love and romantic relationships&nbsp;\u2013 although there are notable exceptions.<ref name=Firth2001/>\n\n[[Harmony (music)|Harmony]] and [[chord progression]]s in pop music are often \"that of [[Classical music|classical]] European [[tonality]], only more simple-minded.\"<ref>Winkler, Peter (1978). \"Toward a theory of pop harmony\", ''In Theory Only'', 4, pp.&nbsp;3\u201326.</ref> Clich\u00e9s include the [[close and open harmony|barbershop quartet-style harmony]] (i.e. ii \u2013 V \u2013 I) and [[blues scale]]-influenced harmony.<ref>Sargeant, p. 198. cited in Winkler (1978), p. 4.</ref> There was a lessening of the influence of traditional views of the [[circle of fifths]] between the mid-1950s and the late 1970s, including less predominance for the [[dominant (music)|dominant]] [[diatonic function|function]].<ref>Winkler (1978), p. 22.</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Development and influence==\n\n===Technology and media===\n\n{{multiple image\n| total_width = 230\n| align = right\n| image1 = Michael Jackson in 1988.jpg\n| width1 = \n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Madonna, Rotterdam, 26-8-1987.jpg\n| width2 = \n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer = [[Michael Jackson]] (left) and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] (right), known respectively as the \"[[Honorific nicknames in popular music|King and Queen of Pop]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2008/oct/28/madonna-pop-art|first=Alan|last=McGee|authorlink=Alan McGee|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=August 20, 2008|accessdate=April 17, 2013|title=Madonna Pop Art}}</ref>\n| direction = \n}}\n\nIn the 1940s improved [[microphone]] design allowed a more intimate singing style and ten or twenty years later, inexpensive and more durable 45 rpm records for singles \"revolutionized the manner in which pop has been disseminated\", which helped to move pop music to \"a record/radio/film star system\".<ref name=Buckley>D. Buckley, \"Pop\" \"II. Implications of technology\", ''Grove Music Online'', retrieved 15 March 2010.</ref> Another technological change was the widespread availability of television in the 1950s; with televised performances, \"pop stars had to have a visual presence\".<ref name=Buckley/> In the 1960s, the introduction of inexpensive, portable [[transistor radio]]s meant that teenagers in the developed world could listen to music outside of the home.<ref name=Buckley/> By the early 1980s, the promotion of pop music had been greatly affected by the rise of music television channels like [[MTV]], which \"favoured those artists such as [[Michael Jackson]] and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] who had a strong visual appeal\".<ref name=Buckley/>\n\n[[Multi-track recording]] (from the 1960s); and [[sampling (music)|digital sampling]] (from the 1980s) have also been utilized as methods for the creation and elaboration of pop music.<ref name=Firth2001/> During the mid-1960s, pop music made repeated forays into new sounds, styles, and techniques that inspired public discourse among its listeners. The word \"progressive\" was frequently used, and it was thought that every song and single was to be a \"progression\" from the last.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hewitt|first1=Paolo|last2=Hellier|first2=John|title=Steve Marriott: All Too Beautiful|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CxhzCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT162|year=2015|publisher=Dean Street Press|isbn=978-1-910570-69-2|page=162}}</ref> [[Music journalism|Music critic]] [[Simon Reynolds]] writes that beginning with 1967, a divide would exist between \"progressive\" pop and \"mass/chart\" pop, a separation which was \"also, broadly, one between boys and girls, middle-class and working-class.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Reynolds|first=Simon|authorlink=Simon Reynolds|title=On Record: Rock, Pop and the Written Word|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lauJAgAAQBAJ|year=2006|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-93951-0|chapter=New Pop and its Aftermath|page=398}}</ref>\n\nThe latter half of the 20th-century included a large-scale trend in American culture in which the boundaries between art and pop music were increasingly blurred.<ref>{{cite book|pp=317, 1233|editor-last=Edmondson|editor-first=Jacqueline|title=Music in American Life: An Encyclopedia of the Songs, Styles, Stars, and Stories that Shaped our Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TQPXAQAAQBAJ|year=2013|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-39348-8}}</ref> Between 1950 and 1970, there was a debate of pop versus art.<ref name=\"PMLoss2015\"/> Since then, certain music publications have embraced the music's legitimacy, a trend referred to as \"[[poptimism]]\".<ref name=\"PMLoss2015\">{{cite web|last1=Loss|first1=Robert|title=No Apologies: A Critique of the Rockist v. Poptimist Paradigm|url=http://www.popmatters.com/column/196122-no-apologies-a-critique-of-the-rockist-v.-poptimist-paradigm/|website=[[PopMatters]]|date=August 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Stylistic evolution===\n[[File:Katy_Perry_2011.jpg|thumb|left|[[Katy Perry]]'s characteristic spinning peppermint swirl dress which she wore during the California Dreams tour|alt=]]\n\nThroughout its development, pop music has absorbed influences from other genres of popular music. Early pop music drew on the [[sentimental ballad]] for its form, gained its use of vocal harmonies from [[gospel music|gospel]] and [[soul music]], instrumentation from [[jazz]] and [[rock music]], orchestration from [[classical music]], tempo from [[dance music]], backing from [[electronic music]], rhythmic elements from [[hip-hop music]], and spoken passages from [[rap music|rap]].<ref name=Firth2001>S. Frith, W. Straw, and J. Street, eds, ''[[Cambridge Companions to Music|The Cambridge Companion to Pop and Rock]]'' (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press), {{ISBN|0-521-55660-0}}, pp.&nbsp;95\u2013105.</ref>{{verification needed|date=February 2017}} In 2016, a ''[[Scientific Reports]]'' study that examined over 464,000 recordings of popular music recorded between 1955 and 2010 found that since the 1960s, pop music had found less variety in pitch progressions, grown average loudness levels,<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1038/srep00521|pmid=22837813|pmc=3405292|title=Measuring the Evolution of Contemporary Western Popular Music|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=2|pages=521|year=2012|last1=Serr\u00e0|first1=Joan|last2=Corral|first2=\u00c1lvaro|last3=Bogu\u00f1\u00e1|first3=Mari\u00e1n|last4=Haro|first4=Mart\u00edn|last5=Arcos|first5=Josep Ll.}}</ref> less diverse instrumentation and recording techniques, and less timbral variety.<ref name=\"Matson\"/> ''[[Scientific American]]''{{'}}s John Matson reported that this \"seems to support the popular anecdotal observation that pop music of yore was \"better\", or at least more varied, than today's top-40 stuff\". However, he also noted that the study may not have been entirely representative of pop in each generation.<ref name=\"Matson\">[http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/observations/is-pop-music-evolving-or-is-it-just-getting-louder/ John Matson, \"Is Pop Music Evolving, or Is It Just Getting Louder?\", ''Scientific American'', 26 July 2012]. Retrieved 30 March 2016</ref>\n\nIn the 1960s, the majority of mainstream pop music fell in two categories: guitar, drum and bass groups or singers backed by a traditional orchestra.<ref>{{cite web|title=Making Arrangements\u2014A Rough Guide To Song Construction & Arrangement, Part 1 |url=http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/1997_articles/oct97/arranging1.html |work=Sound on Sound |accessdate=8 May 2014 |date=October 1997 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140508082609/http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/1997_articles/oct97/arranging1.html |archivedate=8 May 2014 |df= }}</ref> Since early in the decade, it was common for pop producers, songwriters, and engineers to freely experiment with musical form, [[orchestration]], [[reverberation|unnatural reverb]], and other sound effects. Some of the best known examples are [[Phil Spector]]'s [[Wall of Sound]] and [[Joe Meek]]'s use of homemade electronic sound effects for acts like [[the Tornados]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Blake|first=Andrew|editor-last1=Cook|editor-first1=Nicholas|editor-last2=Clarke|editor-first2=Eric|editor-last3=Leech-Wilkinson|editor-first3=Daniel|title=The Cambridge Companion to Recorded Music|chapter=Recording practices and the role of the producer|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xb0hAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA45|date=2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-82796-6|page=45}}</ref> At the same time, pop music on radio and in both American and British film moved away from refined [[Tin Pan Alley]] to more eccentric songwriting and incorporated reverb-drenched rock guitar, symphonic strings, and horns played by groups of properly arranged and rehearsed studio musicians.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pareles|first=Jon|authorlink=Jon Pareles|date=October 31, 2008|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/01/arts/music/01pupp.html?_r=0|title=Orchestral Pop, the Way It Was (More or Less)|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=July 4, 2013}}</ref>  A 2019 study held by [[New York University]] in which 643 participants had to rank how familiar a pop song is to them, songs from the 1960s turned out to be the most memorable, significantly more than songs from recent years 2000 to 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smoothradio.com/news/music/best-decade-pop-music/|title=The greatest decade for pop music has been revealed (according to science)|website=Smooth|language=en|access-date=2019-03-31}}</ref>\n\nBefore the [[progressive pop]] of the late 1960s, performers were typically unable to decide on the artistic content of their music.<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Willis|first=Paul E.|authorlink=Paul Willis|title=Profane Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y7oWBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA219|year=2014|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-6514-7|page=217}}</ref> Assisted by the mid-1960s economic boom, record labels began investing in artists, giving them the freedom to experiment, and offering them limited control over their content and marketing.{{sfn|Moore|2016|p=202}} This situation declined after the late 1970s and would not reemerge until the rise of [[Internet]] stars.{{sfn|Moore|2016|p=202}} [[Indie pop]], which developed in the late 1970s, marked another departure from the glamour of contemporary pop music, with guitar bands formed on the then-novel premise that one could record and release their own music without having to procure a [[record contract]] from a major label.<ref>{{Citation|title=Twee as Fuck: The Story of Indie Pop |first=Nitsuh |last=Abebe |work=Pitchfork Media |date=24 October 2005 |url=http://pitchfork.com/features/articles/6176-twee-as-fuck/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5wjlLnVho?url=http://pitchfork.com/features/articles/6176-twee-as-fuck/ |archivedate=24 February 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n\n[[Latin pop]] rose in popularity in the [[United States]] during the 1950s with early rock and roll success [[Ritchie Valens]], though it truly rose to prominence during the 1970s and 1980s with the likes of [[Los Lobos]].<ref name=\"Portwood Portwood 2019\">{{cite web | last=Portwood | first=Jerry | last2=Portwood | first2=Jerry | title=Ritchie Valens Musical in the Works From Los Lobos' Louie Perez and David Hidalgo | website=Rolling Stone | date=December 12, 2019 | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/ritchie-valens-musical-los-lobos-925326/ | access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref> With later [[Hispanic and Latino Americans]] seeing success within pop music charts, 1990s pop successes stayed popular in both their original genres and in broader pop music. Artists like [[Selena]] saw large-scale pop music presence, and crossover appeal with fans of [[Tejano music]] trailblazers like [[Lydia Mendoza]]; likewise in other genres like [[Lorenzo Antonio]] and [[Sparx (US band)|Sparx]], who are recognized throughout [[Latin America]] as well as within their [[New Mexico music]] repertoire of [[Al Hurricane]] and [[Antonia Apodaca]].<ref>{{cite book | last=Aldama | first=A.J. | last2=Sandoval | first2=C. | last3=Garc\u00eda | first3=P.J. | title=Performing the US Latina and Latino Borderlands | publisher=Indiana University Press | year=2012 | isbn=978-0-253-00295-2 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a7KXaqig1YwC&pg=PA224 | access-date=February 14, 2020 | page=224}}</ref> Musicians like [[Shakira]], [[Ricky Martin]], [[Selena Gomez]], and [[Demi Lovato]] seen lasting mass-appeal within pop music circles. Latin pop hit singles, like \u201c[[Macarena]]\u201d by [[Los del R\u00edo]] and \u201c[[Despacito]]\u201d by [[Luis Fonsi]] have seen record-breaking success on worldwide pop music charts.<ref name=\"Villafa\u00f1e 2017\">{{cite web | last=Villafa\u00f1e | first=Veronica | title=Still No.1, Record-Breaking 'Despacito' Ties 'Macarena' Streak On Hot 100, But Is Snubbed By MTV | website=Forbes | date=August 14, 2017 | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/veronicavillafane/2017/08/14/still-no-1-record-breaking-despacito-ties-macarena-streak-on-hot-100-but-is-snubbed-by-mtv/ | access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe 1980s are commonly remembered for an increase in the use of [[digital recording]], associated with the usage of [[synthesizer]]s, with [[synth-pop]] music and other [[electronic music|electronic]] genres featuring non-traditional instruments increasing in popularity.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/08/29/arts/rap-music-brash-and-swaggering-enters-mainstream.html | work=The New York Times | first=Glenn | last=Collins | title=Rap Music, Brash And Swaggering, Enters Mainstream | date=1988-08-29}}</ref> By 2014, pop music worldwide had been permeated by [[electronic dance music]].<ref name=\"Christgau\"/> In 2018, researchers at the [[University of California, Irvine]], concluded that pop music has become 'sadder' since the 1980s. The elements of [[happiness]] and brightness have eventually been replaced with the electronic beats making the pop music more 'sad yet danceable'.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thefader.com/2018/05/16/sadness-in-pop-music-study|title=New study finds pop music has gotten extremely depressing but also more fun to dance to|work=The FADER|access-date=2018-05-21|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===International spread===\n{{Quote box\n |quote = The story of pop music is largely the story of the intertwining pop culture of the United States and the United Kingdom in the postwar era.\n |source =&nbsp;\u2014 [[Bob Stanley (musician)|Bob Stanley]]<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite web|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|year=2014|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/bn/bn2014-07.php|title=Anti-Rockism's Hall of Fame|work=[[The Barnes & Noble Review]]|accessdate=August 18, 2015}}</ref>\n |quoted = true\n |bgcolor =\n |width = 22%\n |salign = right\n |align = right\n |border = 1px\n |fontsize = 89%\n}}\n\nPop music has been dominated by the American and (from the mid-1960s) British [[music industry|music industries]], whose influence has made pop music something of an international monoculture, but most regions and countries have their own form of pop music, sometimes producing local versions of wider trends, and lending them local characteristics.<ref>J. Kun, ''Audiotopia: Music, Race, and America'' (Berkeley, CA: University of California Press, 2005), {{ISBN|0-520-24424-9}}, p. 201.</ref> Some of these trends (for example [[Europop]]) have had a significant impact of the development of the genre.<ref name=Firth2002>\"Star profiles\" in S. Frith, W. Stray and J. Street, ''The Cambridge Companion to Pop and Rock'' (Cambridge University Press, 2001), {{ISBN|0-521-55660-0}}, pp. 199\u2013200.</ref>\n\nAccording to ''Grove Music Online'', \"Western-derived pop styles, whether coexisting with or marginalizing distinctively local genres, have spread throughout the world and have come to constitute stylistic common denominators in global commercial music cultures\".<ref name=PManuel>P. Manuel, \"Pop. Non-Western cultures 1. Global dissemination\", ''Grove Music Online'', retrieved 14 March 2010.</ref> Some non-Western countries, such as Japan, have developed a thriving pop music industry, most of which is devoted to Western-style pop. Japan has for several years produced a greater quantity of music than everywhere except the US.{{Clarify|reason=vague|date=April 2017}}<ref name=PManuel/> The spread of Western-style pop music has been interpreted variously as representing processes of Americanization, [[Radio Homogenization|homogenization]], modernization, creative appropriation, [[cultural imperialism]], or a more general process of [[globalization]].<ref name=PManuel/>\n\nIn Korea, pop music's influence has led to the birth of [[boy bands]] and [[girl groups]] which have gained overseas renown through both their music and aesthetics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.es/yodona/2015/12/03/565f220b46163ff4308b45c9.html|title=K-Pop, la m\u00fasica y la moda 'rarita' coreana que arrasa la red|date=December 3, 2015|website=ELMUNDO}}</ref> Korean [[co-ed groups]] (mixed gender groups) have not been as successful.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/blog/2016/08/25/why-arent-there-many-mixed-gender-k-pop-groups|title=Why aren't there many mixed gender K-pop groups?|website=SBS PopAsia}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Pop music|Music}}\n* [[Honorific nicknames in popular music]]\n* [[Origins of rock and roll]]\n* [[Popular music pedagogy]]\n* [[List of popular music genres]]\n* [[History of music]]\n* [[Public domain music]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n{{refbegin}}\n* [[Theodor W. Adorno|Adorno, Theodor W.]], (1942) \"On Popular Music\", Institute of Social Research.\n* Bell, John L., (2000) ''The Singing Thing: A Case for Congregational Song'', GIA Publications, {{ISBN|1-57999-100-9}}\n* Bindas, Kenneth J., (1992) ''America's Musical Pulse: Popular Music in Twentieth-Century Society'', Praeger.\n* [[Donald Clarke (writer)|Clarke, Donald]], (1995) ''The Rise and Fall of Popular Music'', St Martin's Press. [https://web.archive.org/web/20071231045026/http://www.musicweb.uk.net/RiseandFall/index.htm ]\n* Dolfsma, Wilfred, (1999) ''Valuing Pop Music: Institutions, Values and Economics'', Eburon.\n* Dolfsma, Wilfred, (2004) ''Institutional Economics and the Formation of Preferences: The Advent of Pop Music'', Edward Elgar Publishing.\n* [[Simon Frith|Frith, Simon]], Straw, Will, Street, John, eds, (2001), ''The Cambridge Companion to Pop and Rock'', Cambridge University Press,\n* [[Simon Frith|Frith, Simon]] (2004) ''Popular Music: Critical Concepts in Media and Cultural Studies'', Routledge.\n* [[Charlie Gillett|Gillett, Charlie]], (1970) ''The Sound of the City. The Rise of Rock and Roll'', Outerbridge & Dienstfrey.\n* Hatch, David and Stephen Millward, (1987), ''From Blues to Rock: an Analytical History of Pop Music'', Manchester University Press, {{ISBN|0-7190-1489-1}}\n* Johnson, Julian, (2002) ''Who Needs Classical Music?: Cultural Choice and Musical Value'', Oxford University Press, {{ISBN|0-19-514681-6}}.\n* [[Jeff Kent (author)|Kent, Jeff]], (1983) ''The Rise and Fall of Rock'', Witan Books, {{ISBN|0-9508981-0-4}}.\n* Lonergan, David F., (2004) ''Hit Records, 1950\u20131975'', Scarecrow Press, {{ISBN|0-8108-5129-6}}.\n* Maultsby, Portia K., (7907) ''Intra- and International Identities in American Popular Music'', Trading Culture.\n* [[Richard Middleton (musicologist)|Middleton, Richard]], (1990) ''Studying Popular Music'', Open University Press.\n* Negus, Bob, (1999) ''Music Genres and Corporate Cultures'', Routledge, {{ISBN|0-415-17399-X}}.\n* [[Henry Pleasants (music critic)|Pleasants, Henry]] (1969) ''Serious Music and All That Jazz'', Simon & Schuster.\n* [[Lillian Roxon|Roxon, Lillian]], (1969) ''Rock Encyclopedia'', Grosset & Dunlap.\n* Shuker, Roy, (2002) ''Popular Music: The Key Concepts'', Routledge, (2nd edn.) {{ISBN|0-415-28425-2}}.\n* Starr, Larry & Waterman, Christopher, (2002) ''American Popular Music: From Minstrelsy to MTV'', Oxford University Press.\n* Watkins, S. Craig, (2005) ''Hip Hop Matters: Politics, Pop Culture, and the Struggle for the Soul of a Movement'', Beacon Press, {{ISBN|0-8070-0982-2}}.\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Pop music}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170407053620/http://musiclife.mobi/filelist/1017/sabrang_%282017%29_mp3/new2old/1 The Consumption of Music and the Expression of Values: A Social Economic Explanation for the Advent of Pop Music], Wilfred Dolfsma, ''[[American Journal of Economics and Sociology]]'', October 1999.\n\n{{Pop music}}\n{{Media culture}}\n{{Western world}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pop Music}}\n[[Category:Pop music| ]]\n[[Category:Western culture]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 1920s]]\n", "name_user": "82.8.45.122", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pop_music"}
{"title_page": "Fred Flintstone and Friends", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Fred Flintstone and Friends\n| image                = Fred Flintstone and Friends.jpg\n| genre                = [[Animation]]\n| runtime              = 30 minutes\n| director             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Charles August Nichols|Charles A. Nichols]]\n* [[William Hanna]]\n* [[Joseph Barbera]]\n}}\n| producer             = {{Plainlist|\n* William Hanna\n* Joseph Barbera\n}}\n| executive_producer   = {{Plainlist|\n* William Hanna\n* Joseph Barbera\n}}\n| presenter            = [[Fred Flintstone]]\n| theme_music_composer = [[Hoyt Curtin]]\n| opentheme            = \"Fred Flintstone and Friends\"\n| country              = United States\n| company              = [[Hanna-Barbera|Hanna-Barbera Productions]]<br>[[Columbia Pictures Television]]\n| distributor          = [[Claster Television|Claster Television Productions]]\n| language             = English\n| network              = [[Broadcast syndication|Syndication]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|1977|10|3}}\n| last_aired           = {{End date|1978|9|1}}\n| num_seasons          = 1\n| num_episodes         = 95\n| list_episodes        = \n| preceded_by          = ''[[The Flintstone Comedy Hour]]''\n| followed_by          = ''[[The New Fred and Barney Show]]''\n| website              = \n}}\n\n'''''Fred Flintstone and Friends''''' is a 30-minute [[Weekday cartoon|weekday animated]] [[anthology series|anthology]] [[wheel series]] and a [[spin-off (media)|spin-off]] of ''[[The Flintstones]]'' produced by [[Hanna-Barbera]] and [[Columbia Pictures Television]] which aired in [[Broadcast syndication|first-run syndication]] from October 3, 1977 to September 1, 1978. The series was packaged by Columbia Pictures Television during the 1977\u201378 television season and was available for barter syndication through [[Claster Television]] through the mid-1980s.<ref name=\"Sobel\">Sobel, Robert (1977). \"Syndicated kidvid lively; top dollar for cartoons\" ''Television/Radio Age'', Vol. 25, No. 2. (August 15, 1977), p. 66.</ref>\n\n[[Henry Corden]] made his official debut as [[Fred Flintstone]]'s ''speaking'' voice on this series after [[Alan Reed]] died in June 1977. Corden had previously appeared as Fred's ''singing'' voice in the theatrical film ''[[The Man Called Flintstone]]'' (1966) and the television specials ''[[Alice in Wonderland or What's a Nice Kid Like You Doing in a Place Like This?]]'' (1966) and ''[[Energy: A National Issue]]'' (1977). He continued providing Fred's voice in future ''Flintstones'' spin-off series and specials, as well as [[Pebbles cereal|Cocoa Pebbles and Fruity Pebbles]] cereal commercials, until his death in 2005.\n\n==Overview==\nThe series is hosted by [[Fred Flintstone]] and featured a repackaging of the following six Hanna-Barbera [[Saturday-morning cartoon|Saturday morning cartoons]] that were originally broadcast by the various networks:\n\n*''[[The Flintstone Comedy Hour]]'' (1972\u20131974) (\"Fred and Barney\" and \"The Bedrock Rockers\" segments)\n*''[[Goober and the Ghost Chasers]]'' (1973\u20131975)\n*''[[Jeannie (TV series)|Jeannie]]'' (1973\u20131975)\n*''[[Partridge Family 2200 A.D.]]'' (1974\u20131975) (re-titled ''The Partridge Family in Outer Space'')\n*''[[The Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm Show]]'' (1971\u20131972)\n*''[[Yogi's Gang]]'' (1973)\n\nThe six series were repackaged from their original half-hour formats into multi-part [[Serial (radio and television)|serialized]] segments which were introduced by Fred on a daily basis (via [[voice-over]]s on brief bumper clips shown in-between segments). The opening title sequence was a composite, using clips from the openings of the various series, along with a new title theme song. Like many animated series created by Hanna-Barbera in the 1970s, the show contained an inferior [[Laugh track#Making their own|laugh track created by the studio]].\n\n==Voice cast==\n* [[Henry Corden]] as [[Fred Flintstone]] (Host), [[The Hillbilly Bears|Paw Rugg]], Dr. Bigot (''Yogi's Gang'')\n* [[Josh Albee]] as Freddy, Jimmy (''Yogi's Gang'')\n* [[Sherry Alberoni]] as Laurie Partridge (''The Partridge Family in Outer Space'')\n* [[Julie Bennett]] as [[Cindy Bear]] (''Yogi's Gang'')\n* [[Joe Besser]] as Babu (''Jeannie'')\n* [[Mel Blanc]] as [[Barney Rubble]], [[Dino (The Flintstones)|Dino]], Zonk, Stub (''The Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm Show'', ''The Flintstone Comedy Hour'')\n* [[Danny Bonaduce]] as Danny Partridge (''Goober and the Ghost Chasers'', ''The Partridge Family in Outer Space'')\n* [[Tom Bosley]] as Commadore Phineas P. Fibber (''Yogi's Gang'')\n* [[Daws Butler]] as [[Yogi Bear]], [[Huckleberry Hound]], [[Quick Draw McGraw]], [[Snagglepuss]], [[Wally Gator]], [[Peter Potamus]], [[Augie Doggie and Doggie Daddy|Augie Doggie]], [[Hokey Wolf]], [[Lippy the Lion & Hardy Har Har|Lippy the Lion]], [[Baba Looey]] (''Yogi's Gang'')\n* [[Tommy Cook (actor)|Tommy Cook]] as S. Melvin Farthinghill (''Jeannie'')\n* [[Suzanne Crough]] as Tracy Partridge (''Goober and the Ghost Chasers'', ''The Partridge Family in Outer Space'')\n* [[Jerry Dexter]] as Ted (''Goober and the Ghost Chasers'')\n* [[Susan Dey]] as Laurie Partridge (''Goober and the Ghost Chasers'')\n* [[Micky Dolenz]] as Wonderful Wayne, Spotless Sam (''The Partridge Family in Outer Space'')\n* Carl Esser as Fabian (''The Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm Show'', ''The Flintstone Comedy Hour'')\n* [[Brian Forster]] as Chris Partridge (''Goober and the Ghost Chasers'', ''The Partridge Family in Outer Space'')\n* [[Joan Gerber]] as Shirley Partridge (''The Partridge Family in Outer Space'')\n* [[Virginia Gregg]] as Gossipy Witch of the West (''Yogi's Gang'')\n* [[Mark Hamill]] as Corey Anders (''Jeannie'')\n* [[Jo Ann Harris]] as Tina (''Goober and the Ghost Chasers'')\n* [[Gay Autterson|Gay Hartwig]] as [[Betty Rubble]], Wiggy, Cindy (''The Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm Show'', ''The Flintstone Comedy Hour'')\n* [[Bob Hastings]] as Henry Glopp (''Jeannie'')\n* [[Rose Marie]] as Lotta Litter (''Yogi's Gang'')\n* [[Mitzi McCall]] as Penny (''The Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm Show'', ''The Flintstone Comedy Hour'')\n* Chuck McLenan as Keith Partridge (''The Partridge Family in Outer Space'')\n* [[Julie McWhirter]] as Jeannie (''Jeannie''),  Marion (''The Partridge Family in Outer Space'')\n* [[Allan Melvin]] as [[Magilla Gorilla]], Mr. Sloppy, Mr. Neat, Professor Haggling (''Yogi's Gang'')\n* [[Don Messick]] as [[Boo-Boo Bear]], [[Ranger Smith]], [[Touch\u00e9 Turtle and Dum Dum|Touch\u00e9 Turtle]], [[Atom Ant]], [[Squiddly Diddly]], Mayor of Smog City (''Yogi's Gang''), Schleprock (''The Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm Show'', ''The Flintstone Comedy Hour'')\n* [[Jay North]] as [[Bamm-Bamm Rubble]] (''The Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm Show'', ''The Flintstone Comedy Hour'')\n* [[Alan Reed]] as [[Fred Flintstone]] (''The Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm Show'', ''The Flintstone Comedy Hour'')\n* [[Ronnie Schell]] as Gilly (''Goober and the Ghost Chasers'')\n* [[Hal Smith (actor)|Hal Smith]] as J. Wanton Vandal, Smiley the Hobo (''Yogi's Gang'')\n* [[John Stephenson (actor)|John Stephenson]] as [[Augie Doggie and Doggie Daddy|Doggie Daddy]], [[Lippy the Lion & Hardy Har Har|Hardy Har Har]], Mr. Cheerful, Greedy Genie, Hilarious P. Prankster, Envy Brother #2, Captain Swashbuckle Swipe, Fumbo Jumbo the Masked Avenger, Mr. Hothead, Professor Bickering (''Yogi's Gang''), Mr. Slate, Noodles (''The Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm Show'', ''The Flintstone Comedy Hour''), Haji (''Jeannie''), Reuben Kincaid (''The Partridge Family in Outer Space'')\n* Mickey Stevens as [[Pebbles Flintstone]] (''The Flintstone Comedy Hour'')\n* [[Sally Struthers]] as [[Pebbles Flintstone]] (''The Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm Show'')\n* [[Jean Vander Pyl]] as [[Wilma Flintstone]] (''The Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm Show'', ''The Flintstone Comedy Hour''), [[The Hillbilly Bears|Maw Rugg]] (''Yogi's Gang'')\n* [[Janet Waldo]] as Mrs. Anders (''Jeannie'')\n* [[Lennie Weinrib]] as Smokestack Smog (''Yogi's Gang''), Moonrock, Bronto (''The Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm Show'', ''The Flintstone Comedy Hour''), Jolly Joe (''The Partridge Family in Outer Space'')\n* [[Frank Welker]] as Orbit, Veenie (''The Partridge Family in Outer Space'')\n* [[Jesse White (actor)|Jesse White]] as Peter D. Cheater (''Yogi's Gang'')\n* [[Paul Winchell]] as Goober (''Goober and the Ghost Chasers''), Sheik of Selfishness (''Yogi's Gang'')\n\n==Weekly airing schedule==\nThe following segments were broadcast in [[parity (mathematics)|odd weeks]]:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Monday !! Tuesday !! Wednesday !! Thursday !! Friday\n|-\n| ''Jeannie'' <small>[Part 1]</small><br>''Yogi's Gang'' <small>[Part 1]</small> || ''Jeannie'' <small>[Part 2]</small><br>''Yogi's Gang'' <small>[Part 2]</small> ||  ''Goober and the Ghost Chasers'' <small>[Part 1]</small><br>''Yogi's Gang'' <small>[Part 3]</small> || ''Goober and the Ghost Chasers'' <small>[Part 2]</small><br>''The Partridge Family in Outer Space'' <small>[Part 1]</small> || ''Goober and the Ghost Chasers'' <small>[Part 3]</small><br>''The Partridge Family in Outer Space'' <small>[Part 2]</small>\n|}\n\nThe following segments were broadcast in [[parity (mathematics)|even weeks]]:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Monday !! Tuesday !! Wednesday !! Thursday !! Friday\n|-\n| ''The Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm Show'' || ''The Flintstone Comedy Hour'' || ''The Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm Show'' || ''The Flintstone Comedy Hour'' || ''The Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm Show''\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Hanna\u2013Barbera's World of Super Adventure]]'', a later rerun anthology series\n* ''[[USA Cartoon Express]]'', a daily cartoon block that featured some of these series\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0242201|title=Fred Flintstone and Friends}}\n* {{tv.com show|fred-flintstone-and-friends|Fred Flintstone and Friends}}\n* [http://www.bcdb.com/cartoon/11076-Fred_Flintstone_And_Friends.html ''Fred Flintstone and Friends''] at [[The Big 